{"title_page": "Lagos, Portugal", "text_new": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n| type            = municipality\n|official_name      = Lagos\n|image_flag         = Pt-lgs1.png\n|image_shield       = LGS.png\n| image_skyline           = {{Photomontage\n| photo1a                 = Vista Centro Hist\u00f3rico de Lagos (cropped).jpg\n| photo2a                 = Igreja de Santo Ant\u00f3nio, Lagos, Portugal 2 (cropped).jpg\n| photo2b                 = Algarve Bucht Lagos (27637090891).jpg\n| photo2c                 = Lagos (41611145272).jpg\n| photo3a                 = Lagos fortress pic 01.jpg\n| photo3b                 = Lagos (40939860814).jpg\n| spacing                 = 2\n| position                = center\n| color_border            = white\n| color                   = white\n| size                    = 280\n| foot_montage            =\n}}\n|image_location     = LocalLagos.svg\n|region             = [[Algarve]]\n|CIM                = [[Algarve]]\n|district           = [[Faro District|Faro]]\n|parishes           = [[#Human geography|4]]\n|leader_name        = Joaquina Matos\n|leader_party       = [[Socialist Party (Portugal)|PS]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|37|6|10|N|8|40|22|W|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = 212.99\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 31,049\n|patron             = \n|postal_code        = 8600\n|area_code          = 282\n|website            = http://www.cm-lagos.pt\n}}\n'''Lagos''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8la\u0263u\u0283|-|Pt-pt Lagos FF.ogg}}; literally \"lakes\"; {{lang-cel-x-proto|Lacobriga}}) is a municipality at the mouth of [[Bensafrim River]] and along the [[Atlantic Ocean]], in the Barlavento region of the [[Algarve]], in southern [[Portugal]].<ref>Detail Regional Map, Algarve-Southern Portugal, {{ISBN|3-8297-6235-6}}</ref> The population in 2011 was 31,049,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0|title=Statistics Portugal|website=www.ine.pt|accessdate=28 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115205227/http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0|archivedate=15 November 2016}}</ref> in an area of 212.99&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The main town of Lagos (which includes only the parish of S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o e Santa Maria) has a population of approximately 22,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ine.pt/scripts/flex_v10/Main.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-22 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109155045/http://www.ine.pt/scripts/flex_v10/Main.html |archivedate=2013-11-09 }}</ref> Typically, these numbers increase during the summer months, with the influx of visiting tourists and seasonal residents. While the majority of the population lives along the coast and works in tourism and services, the inland region is sparsely inhabited, with the majority of the people working in agriculture and forestry.\n\nLagos is one of the most visited cities in the Algarve and Portugal, due to its variety of tourist-friendly beaches, rock formations ([[Ponta da Piedade]]), bars, restaurants and hotels, renowned for its vibrant summer nightlife and parties.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} Yet, Lagos is also a historic centre of the Portuguese [[Portuguese Discoveries|Age of Discovery]], frequent home of [[Henry the Navigator]], historical shipyard and, at one time, centre of the European slave trade.<ref>{{cite book |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=Ziv7J90u-mAC |page=14 }} |title=A Long and Uncertain Journey: The 27,000 Mile Voyage of Vasco Da Gama - Joan E. Goodman, Tom McNeely |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref> In 2012, travel website [[TripAdvisor]], classified Lagos as the number one travel destination, on a list of \"15 destinations on the rise\" worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tripadvisor.com/InfoCenter-a_ctr.ontherise__5F__world__5F__en |title=15 destinations on the rise |publisher=Tripadvisor.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lagos43 kopie.jpg|thumb|left|235px|A painting from the 16th century showing a caravel being provisioned in the port of Lagos depicting Africans and Europeans]]\n[[File:Caravela Boa Esperan\u00e7a - Lagos.JPG|thumb|left|235px|Replica of the caravel Boa Esperan\u00e7a]]\n[[File:Mercado de Escravos.jpg|thumb|left|235px|Lagos's slave market. Built in 1444, it was colonial Europe's first slave market]]\nLagos is an ancient maritime town with more than 2000 years of history. The name ''Lagos'' comes from a [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] settlement, derived from the Latin ''[[Lacobriga]]'', the name of the settlement was established during the pre-[[Punics|Punic]] civilizations. It became an early settlement of the [[Carthage|Carthaginians]], who recruited Celtic tribesmen in their war against the Romans (the [[Punic Wars]]). Owing to its already important harbour, it was colonized by the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] and integrated into the Roman province of [[Lusitania]], becoming known as Lacobriga. [[Quintus Sertorius]], a rebellious Roman general, helped by the Lusitanians of Lacobriga (who had been oppressed under Roman Generals and members of [[Lucius Cornelius Sulla]] party), successfully defeated the Roman army of [[Quintus Caecilius Metellus Pius|Caecilius Metellus Pius]] probably at nearby [[Monte Moli\u00e3o]].\n\nWith the fall of Rome, the town of Lagos was occupied in the 6th century by the [[Visigoths]] from the [[Visigoths#Kingdom of Toledo|Kingdom of Toledo]] and later by the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]].\n\nThe [[Moors]] arrived in the 8th century from North Africa, renaming the settlement ''Zawaia'' (meaning ''lago'', or ''lake'').  It became part of the much larger coastal region of ''al-Gharb'', which eventually became known as the ''algarve''. The Moors fortified the town  with [[Lagos Castle]] and established important trade links to Northern Africa from their bases in the Iberian peninsula. In 1174, the local [[W\u0101li]] gave permission for the Christian peoples to construct a church dedicated to S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o Baptista, which was built outside the town's walls (becoming the oldest church in the Algarve).\n\n===Kingdom===\nEven as King [[Afonso Henriques]] advanced to the south, the Christian [[Reconquista]] never made it into Algarve and Alentejo, and remained under Moorish control. King [[Sancho I of Portugal|Sancho I]], with the support of Crusader forces used Lagos as a stepping stone to attack the fortress of Alv\u00f4r.<ref>\nCUP (1970), p.95</ref> Zawaia was eventually captured by King [[Afonso III of Portugal]] in 1241, but was only taken definitively in 1249. From this period on the King began self-styling himself as the ''\"King of Portugal and the Algarve\"'', stressing the fact that the Algarve (which had for so long been ruled by the Moors as a foreign country) had been annexed into the dominion of the Portuguese.\nLagos became an independent jurisdiction under the rule of King [[Peter I of Portugal|Peter I]] in 1361.\n\nKing [[John I of Portugal|John I]] assembled his fleet in the harbour of Lagos, before setting sail for the siege and [[Conquest of Ceuta|conquest of the city of Ceuta]] in 1415. This was the first step in opening the Muslim world to medieval Europe, which in fact led to the [[Age of Discovery]] with Portuguese explorers sailing across the whole world. By the 15th century, Lagos became the centre of Portuguese maritime exploration, with ships ordered south to trace the shoreline of Africa in order to find routes to India. [[Infante]] [[Henry the Navigator]], third son of King John, lived most of the time in Lagos. From here he directed expeditions to [[Morocco]] and to the western coast of [[Africa]] with [[caravel]]s, [[lateen]]-rigged ships with excellent seafaring capabilities. Lagos was also the home port for [[Gil Eanes]] who was the first to sail beyond [[Cape Bojador]] in 1434, after a failed attempt in 1433 that put him out of favour with the, then considered the end of the world. The act of rounding the Cape, much like the later rounding of the [[Cape of Good Hope]], permitted Eanes (and the navigators that followed) to advance into the African subcontinent. When, by 1443, Lan\u00e7arote (then fiscal officer of the crown) had sailed as far as [[Arguim]] and brought back 275 Africans, the Portuguese had sufficient slaves to relieve the perpetual handicap of agricultural labour.<ref>CUP (1970), p.190</ref>\n\nOver the following decades, news of discoveries and achievements, and ships loaded with spices and goods would flow into the port of Lagos.  It was also the gateway for the first African [[slave]]s into post-medieval Europe.<ref name=\"H. Morse Stephens 1891, p.149\">H. Morse Stephens (1891), p.149</ref> Even before Africa was opened-up to the Portuguese, the seamen of Lagos were already enthusiastic slave-catchers.<ref>David Birmingham (2003), p. 27</ref> From the first slave markets in Lagos (the ''Mercado de Escravos'', which opened in 1444), many Africans were dispersed throughout Europe, bringing a considerable income to the Portuguese monarchy and merchant classes, as well as cheap labour force.<ref name=\"H. Morse Stephens 1891, p.149\"/> As the major sponsor of these expeditions, Prince Henry received one-fifth of the selling price of every slave. The demand for the indentured labour force was so high that, by 1450, profit on [[Mauritania]]n slaves was 700 percent.<ref>David Birmingham (2003), p. 29</ref>  The discovery of gold by Alfonso Gon\u00e7ales also increased activities in Lagos, whose residents petitioned the Infante Henry to establish a trading company to pursue gold deposits in the region.<ref name=\"Kerr1\">Robert Kerr (1844), p.189</ref> This included Juan Dias (ancestor of [[Bartolomeu Dias]] who rounded the Cape of Good Hope), [[Gil Eanes]], [[Lan\u00e7arote de Freitas]], Estevan Alfonso and Rodrigo Alvarez, who provisioned a squadron of six caravels to travel to isle of Gar\u00e7as in 1444, but returned with 150 Africans.<ref name=Kerr1/>\n[[File:Centro_de_Lagos.png|thumb|235px|right|The historic centre of Lagos]]\nFollowing the death of Prince Henry, and the expansion into the Atlantic and New World, the port of Lagos continued to receive shipments of goods and slaves, but its role began to decrease. Lisbon, began to prosper, with ships returning directly from the colonies of the Azores, Madeira and Brazil, while trading houses began to relocate to the capital. But, even as the wealth arrived in Lisbon and Lagos, the ostentation was widely on display in the royal residences.<ref>David Birmingham (2003), p. 30</ref>\n\nKing [[Sebastian of Portugal|Sebastian]], obsessed with his plans for a great crusade against the [[Kingdom of Fez]], assembled a huge fleet in Lagos in 1578.<ref>H. Morse Stephens (1891), p.253</ref> During this ill-fated attempt he and most of Portugal's nobility were killed in the [[Battle of Ksar El Kebir]] in Morocco, eventually causing a [[1580 Portuguese succession crisis|succession crisis]], that eventually resulted in the [[Iberian Union]].\n\nWhen Portugal came under Spanish rule, the Portuguese coast became a target for the English fleet.  Lagos, close to the Spanish naval base of [[C\u00e1diz]], was attacked by Sir [[Francis Drake]] in the late 1580s, but was defended by its inhabitants, resulting in Drakes sack of [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]].<ref>CUP (1970), p.275</ref> But, the coast was under regular attack of other [[pirate]]s and [[Privateer|corsairs]], in addition to the Spanish who bombarded the Algarve during the [[Portuguese Restoration War]] (1640\u20131668), which led to the construction of a string of forts all along the coast. One of them was the late-17th-century ''Ponta da Bandeira Fort'' in Lagos, which was completed between 1679 and 1690 (according to the stone inscription over the main door).\n\nFrom 1576 to 1755, Lagos was a high-profile capital of the Algarve, until the old Portuguese town was destroyed by the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake|earthquake and tsunami of 1755]]. Although some walls from the 16th century still remain, as well as the governor's [[castle]], many of the buildings are from the 17th century.\n\nTwo well-known naval battles took place off Lagos, reflecting its strategic location: in the [[Battle of Lagos (1693)]] a French flotilla defeated a combined Anglo-Dutch force, while in the [[Battle of Lagos (1759)]] a British force defeated a French force.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Dona Ana beach, Lagos.jpg|thumb|right|235px|''Dona Ana Beach (Praia Dona Ana)'']]\n[[File:Praia_do_Pinh\u00e3o.JPG|thumb|left|150px|Pinh\u00e3o beach]]\n[[File:Praia do Porto de M\u00f3s.jpg|thumb|235px|right|Porto de M\u00f3s beach (Praia do Porto de M\u00f3s) is one of the most popular beaches in Lagos, along with Dona Ana and Meia Praia]]\n\n===Physical geography===\nBy its geographical position (east-northeast to west-southwest orientation) and lithological diversity, the Algarve stands out as a unique [[stratigraphy|stratigraphic]] and [[Morphotectonics|morpho-tectonic]] region.<ref name=\"Episodes\">M. Cach\u00e3o, P. Terrinha, A. Santos (2005), p.179-180</ref> A peripheral [[Carboniferous]] unit of the [[Variscan orogeny]], it constitutes the [[Mesozoic]] and [[Cenozoic]] sedimentary layers, deposited onto two totally distinct superimposed basins.<ref name=Episodes/> Between the Middle-Upper [[Triassic]] to [[Hettangian]], sediments evolved from continental ([[fluvial]] red [[sandstone]]) to shallow marine over the entire region, which included instances of evaporates, tholeiite fissural [[magma]]s, lava flows, [[volcanic ash]] and [[pyroclast]]s.<ref name=Episodes/>\n\nThe area of Lagos, conforms to the Middle [[Miocene]] Lagos-Portim\u00e3o formation (a band that extends along the coast from Lagos to [[Albufeira Municipality|Albufeira]], abutting the Serra do Caldeir\u00e3o to the north) and which corresponds to marine sedimentation over relatively stable, but a minorly deformed limestone shelf platform.<ref name=Episodes/><ref name=\"Forst\">Markus H. Forst, Thomas C. Brachert and Joiio Pais (2000), p.290</ref><ref name=\"JPais\">J. Pais et al. (2000), p.279</ref> A period of calm during the intra-Miocene (of approximately 2.4 Ma) led to generalized exposure and development of [[karst]], that influences the present day coastline.<ref name=Episodes/><ref name=JPais/> The conspicuous horizontal bending of this profile in the cliffs of Lagos, much like the remainder of the Lagos-Portim\u00e3o formation, is formed by alternating bands of [[siliciclastic]] and [[calcareous]] [[lithology|lithologies]].<ref name=Forst/> The low degree of cementation in the layers causes a high degree of instability of the cliffs.<ref name=Forst/> The littoral and cliff sands are dominated by various [[bivalvia|bivalve]] organisms, [[bryozoa]]ns, larger [[Benthic zone|benthic]] [[Foraminifera|foraminifers]] and [[Coralline algae]]with minor additions of [[Sea urchin|echinoids]] and [[Balanidae|balanids]] implying a shallow-water depositional system of a warm-temperate climatic regime.<ref name=Forst/> The locality of Cerro das M\u00f3s, from where a large [[Crocodile|crocodilian]] (''[[False gharial|Tomistoma schlegelii]]'') tooth was collected long ago,<ref>M.T. Antunes et al. (1981), p.9-38</ref> has also produced some [[Toothed whale|Odontoceti]] teeth. These may be dated from the [[Serravallian]], which, constitute the oldest marine mammal occurrence in Algarve.<ref name=JPais/><ref>M. Estevens (2000), p.271-280</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n{{Weather box|location = Lagos, Portugal\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n\n|Jan high C = 15.0\n|Feb high C = 16.1\n|Mar high C = 17.8\n|Apr high C = 20.0\n|May high C = 22.2\n|Jun high C = 25.0\n|Jul high C = 27.8\n|Aug high C = 27.8\n|Sep high C = 26.1\n|Oct high C = 22.2\n|Nov high C = 18.9\n|Dec high C = 16.1\n\n|Jan mean C = 10.6\n|Feb mean C = 13.3\n|Mar mean C = 14.4\n|Apr mean C = 16.7\n|May mean C = 18.3\n|Jun mean C = 21.7\n|Jul mean C = 23.9\n|Aug mean C = 23.9\n|Sep mean C = 22.8\n|Oct mean C = 19.4\n|Nov mean C = 16.1\n|Dec mean C = 13.3\n\n|Jan low C = 6.1\n|Feb low C = 10.0\n|Mar low C = 11.1\n|Apr low C = 12.8\n|May low C = 13.9\n|Jun low C = 17.8\n|Jul low C = 20.0\n|Aug low C = 20.0\n|Sep low C = 18.9\n|Oct low C = 16.1\n|Nov low C = 12.8\n|Dec low C = 10.0\n\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 100\n|Feb precipitation mm = 77\n|Mar precipitation mm = 57\n|Apr precipitation mm = 45\n|May precipitation mm = 30\n|Jun precipitation mm = 16\n|Jul precipitation mm = 2\n|Aug precipitation mm = 2\n|Sep precipitation mm = 16\n|Oct precipitation mm = 58\n|Nov precipitation mm = 90\n|Dec precipitation mm = 102\n\n|source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name=Weatherbase>{{cite web\n|url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=592905&cityname=Lagos-Faro |title =Weatherbase: Historical Weather for Lagos, Portugal|publisher=Weatherbase|year=2020}}\nRetrieved on April 10, 2020.\n</ref>|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Ecoregions/Protected areas===\nLagos has many natural interest sites, including:\n* ''Ponta da Piedade'' ({{lang-en|Mercy Point}})\n* ''Grutas da Costa d'Oiro'' ({{lang-en|Golden Coast Grottos}})\n* ''Laguna de Alvor'' ({{lang-en|Lagoon of Alvor}})\n*\"Bravura Dam\" {{lang-en|Bravura Dam}})\n* ''Mata Nacional de Bar\u00e3o de S.Jo\u00e3o'' ({{lang-en|National Forest of the Baron of Saint John}}), representing a varied flora that includes Pine (''[[Pinaceae]]''), Acacia (''[[Acacia]]''), Eucalyptus (''[[Eucalyptus]]'') and Strawberry trees (''[[Arbutus unedo]]''), with six pedestrian trails and six campsites. In the zone of Pedra Branca, is a [[Paleolithic]] [[menhir]], called the Menhir of Pedro do Galo, accessible through the pedestrian trails, visitors can use the tables and picnicking areas near the guardhouse for barbecues, while small children have access to a playground. A public sports field and 100 metre interval obstacle course was also constructed to attract activity, near the picnic area.\n\n{{wide image|Bravura_Dam_-_Lagos,_Portugal.png|850px|The Bravura Dam, in the parish of Bensafrim}}\n\n====Beaches====\n[[File:Vista de Lagos.JPG|thumb|right|235px|A view of Lagos and the Meia Praia beach in the background]]\n* ''Meia Praia'' (''Half Beach'') \u2014the most popular tourist beach, consisting of soft, white sand, Meia Praia is one of the largest open bays in Europe, resulting in calm seas, permitting conditions for many nautical sports, while cliffs provide sheltered coves from strong windy conditions;\n* ''Praia Solaria'' (''Sunny Beach'');\n* ''Praia da Batata'' (''Potato Beach'') \u2014 a small beach tucked between two small cliffs (where the river meets the Atlantic Ocean), it is known for the small music festivals that take place there during summer;\n* ''Praia dos Estudantes'' (''Students' Beach'');\n* ''Praia da Dona Ana'' (''[[Don (honorific)|Dona]] Ana Beach'') -its areal is slightly thicker than the beaches in the surrounding area and it is surrounded by striking rock formations. At high tide the beach is split by the geomorphology of the cliffs;\n* ''Praia do Canavial'' (''Canavial Beach'');\n* ''Praia de Camilo'' (''Camilo Beach'');\n* ''Praia da Luz'' (''Beach of Light'') - located in the parish of [[Praia da Luz|Luz]], the beach is bounded in the east by ''Rocha Negra'' ({{lang-en|Black Rock}}), providing summer vactioners with a popular escape during the summer.\n* ''Praia da Balan\u00e7a''- located after ''Praia da Boneca'' and ''Praia dos Pinheiros'', it's a sandy cove enclosed by towering cliffs.<ref name=\"Seabookings\">{{cite web |title=Watersports and boat tours in Lagos |url=https://www.seabookings.com/destination/portugal/35-lagos |website=Seabookings }}</ref>\n\n==Sustainable tourism==\nIn 2012 Lagos received the QualityCoast Gold Award for its efforts to become a sustainable tourism destination. Because of this award, Lagos has been selected for inclusion in the global atlas for sustainable tourism [[DestiNet]].\n<ref>[http://www.qualitycoast.info/brochure/qc2012.pdf Sustainable Tourism Destination EUCC] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170924112831/http://www.qualitycoast.info/brochure/qc2012.pdf |date=2017-09-24 }}\n</ref>\n\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"20\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right;\"\n|\n{{stack|\n{{Historical populations\n|title = Population of<br>Lagos<br><small>(1801 - 2011)</small>\n| 1801 | 9789\n| 1849 | 11012\n| 1900 | 13937\n| 1930 | 16210\n| 1960 | 17060\n| 1981 | 19700\n| 1991 | 21526\n| 2001 | 25398\n| 2009 | 29298\n| 2011 | 30755\n}}\n}}\n|}\n\n===Human geography===\nThe municipality of Lagos is located approximately {{convert|35|km|0|abbr=off}} east of the [[Cape St. Vincent]] coast, along the southern coast of the Algarve. It is surrounded along its borders by the municipalities of [[Vila do Bispo Municipality|Vila do Bispo]] (to the west), [[Aljezur Municipality|Aljezur]] (to the northwest), [[Monchique Municipality|Monchique]] (to the northeast) and  [[Portim\u00e3o Municipality|Portim\u00e3o]] (to the east).\n\nTo the north of Lagos is the road to [[Silves Municipality, Portugal|Silves]], the first capital of Algarve, [[Monchique (parish)|Monchique]] (spa town/mountain), [[Vila Nova de Milfontes|Milfontes]], a coastal town and port/harbour of the city of [[Sines, Portugal|Sines]], that winds through the scenic protected landscape of the Southwest Natural Park (Costa Sudoeste Alentejana e Vicentina).\n\nAdministratively, the municipality is divided into 4 civil parishes (''[[freguesia (Portugal)|freguesias]]''):<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 59|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=24 July 2014|author=Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica|language=Portuguese|author-link=Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica }}</ref>\n* [[Bensafrim e Bar\u00e3o de S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o]]\n* Lagos (S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o e Santa Maria)\n* [[Praia da Luz|Luz]] which includes the separate villages of [[Alm\u00e1dena]] and [[Espiche]].\n* Odi\u00e1xere\n\n====Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities====\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Portugal}}\nLagos is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|POR}} [[Torres Vedras Municipality|Torres Vedras]], district of [[Lisbon (district)|Lisbon]], Portugal\n*{{flagicon|Azores}} [[Ribeira Grande (Azores)|Ribeira Grande]], island of [[S\u00e3o Miguel Island|S\u00e3o Miguel]], [[Azores]]\n*{{flagicon|CPV}} [[Ribeira Grande de Santiago, Cape Verde (municipality)|Ribeira Grande de Santiago]], island of [[Santiago, Cape Verde|Santiago]], [[Cape Verde]]\n*{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Palos de la Frontera]], autonomous community of [[Andalusia]], [[Spain]]\n*{{flagicon|MAR}} [[Ksar El Kebir]], city in the province of [[Larache]], [[Morocco]]\n*{{flagicon|NLD}} [[Sassenheim]], town in the province of [[South-Holland]], [[Netherlands]]\n\n{{wide image|Lagos_2_copy.jpg|2000px|Panoramic view of Lagos's Avenida dos Descobrimentos}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Lagos's Marina.jpg|thumb|right|235px|Lagos's marina]]\nLagos' economy, like many coastal towns in Portugal, has always been closely linked to the sea, and [[fishing]] has been an important activity since very ancient times. Since 1960, the city has embraced [[tourism]], which has become its most important economic activity. It has beautiful beaches, good climate, the sea, a scenic coastline, and historical patrimony.\n\nThe Marina de Lagos has 460 berths and has become an important centre for long-distance cruisers, and it is also known for its modern drawbridge.\n\nLagos also has numerous cultural and night-life entertainment venues.\n\nLagos Station is the western terminus of the railway line from [[Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio Municipality|Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio]] (via [[Tavira Municipality|Tavira]] and [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]]). The passenger train service is operated by [[Comboios de Portugal]] (CP). Connections are available at Tunes for trains to Lisbon and Porto.\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Menir_da_Cabe\u00e7a_do_Rochedo_-_Lagos_-_10-05-2018.jpg|thumb|235px|right|The obelisk-like [[Menir of Cabe\u00e7a do Rochedo]], representing the Neolithic history of the settlements of Lagos]]\n[[File:Muralha_de_Lagos.jpg|thumb|right|235px|The [[Castle of Lagos|walls]] of the old city of Lagos, that extended around the old quarter encircling the central part of Santa Maria and S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o]]\n[[File:Lagos_a%C3%A9ria.jpg|thumb|235px|right|Aerial view of Lagos]]\n[[File:Igreja de Santo Ant\u00f3nio - Lagos.JPG|190px|right|thumb|The two towers of Santo Ant\u00f3nio's Church, which also has a museum inside]]\n[[File:Train at lagos station Portugal.jpg|thumb|right|235px|Train at lagos station Portugal]]\n\n===Prehistoric===\n* Menhir of Cabe\u00e7o do Rochedo ({{lang-pt|Menir da Cabe\u00e7o do Rocheado}})\n\n===Civic===\n* Barracks of the Guarda Fiscal of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Quartel e Posto da Guarda Fiscal}})\n* Building of the [[Caixa Geral de Dep\u00f3sitos]] ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio da Caixa Geral de Depositos}})\n* Building of the Correios, Tel\u00e9grafos e Telefonos ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio dos Correios, Tel\u00e9grafos e Telefones de Lagos}})\n* Building of the Portagem ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio Antigo da Portagem}})\n* District Courthouse/Palace of Justice ({{lang-pt|Tribunal da Comarca/Pal\u00e1cio da Justi\u00e7a}})\n* District Jailhouse of Lagos/Cultural Centre of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Cadeia Comarc\u00e3 de Lagos/Centro Cultural}})\n* D. Maria Bridge ({{lang-pt|Ponte Dona Maria}})\n* Fonte Coberta Dam ({{lang-pt|Barragem da Fonte Coberta}})\n* Gil Eanes Secondary/Commercial-Industrial School ({{lang-pt|Escola Industrial e Comercial de Lagos/Escola Secund\u00e1ria Gil Eanes}})\n* Hotel Tivolli Lagos ({{lang-pt|Hotel de Lagos}})\n* Municipal Hall of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio dos Pa\u00e7os do Concelho}})\n* Lighthouse of Ponta da Piedade ({{lang-pt|Farol da Ponta da Piedade}})\n* Pillory of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Pelourinho de Lagos}})\n* Regional Museum of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Museu Regional de Lagos}}) - this modest regional museum is located next to the church of Santo Ant\u00f3nio.,<ref>[http://www.casabelamoura.com/downloadcenter/CulturalHeritageAlgarve.pdf Guide to the cultural heritage of the Algarve] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304025700/http://www.casabelamoura.com/downloadcenter/CulturalHeritageAlgarve.pdf |date=2016-03-04 }}, By Turismo of Portugal:Algarve, {{oclc|860570547}}</ref> housing the [[Eclecticism|eclectic]] collection of archaeological finds from prehistory and the [[Neolithic]], in addition to minerals, Roman mosaics, Moorish oil-lamps and pottery.  The [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] section includes exhibits from life in the Algarve, that includes not only residential, but also military artefacts, such as swords, muskets and cannonballs, and the [[foral]] (''[[charter]]'') issued by King [[Manuel I of Portugal|Manuel]] for Lagos. Religious artefacts are also prominent in the displays, that include the sacerdotal vestments worn by the [[canon (priest)|canon]]s who said Holy Mass to King Sebastian (before he left on his ill-fated conquest of Morocco), and a [[diptych]] (dating from the 16th century) with scenes from the [[Annunciation]] and [[Presentation of Jesus at the Temple]].\n* Slave Market/Customshoues of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Mercado de Escravos/Vedoria/Alf\u00e2ndega de Lagos}})\n\n===Military===\n* Bulwark of Alcaria/Freiras ({{lang-pt|Baluarte da Alcaria/das Freiras}})\n* Bulwark of Porta dos Quartos ({{lang-pt|Baluarte da Porta dos Quartos}})\n* Bulwark of Santa Maria/Porta da Vila ({{lang-pt|Baluarte de Santa Maria/da Porta da Vila}})\n* Bulwark of S\u00e3o Francisco/Jogo da Bola ({{lang-pt|Baluarte de S\u00e3o Francisco/do Jogo da Bola}})\n* Castle of Senhora da Luz ({{lang-pt|Castelo da Senhora da Luz}})\n* Fort of Meia Praia ({{lang-pt|Forte da Meia Praia}})\n* Fort of Ponta da Bandeira ({{lang-pt|Forte da Ponta da Bandeira}}) - also known as the '''Forte do Pau da Bandeira''', the '''Forte de Nossa Senhora da Penha de Fran\u00e7a''' or the '''Forte do Registo''', the fort, which guarded the entrance to the harbour, was originally dedicated to the ''Santa Virgem Senhora da Penha de Fran\u00e7a'' (to which it was referred).<ref>''Ponta da Bandeira'' (or ''Pau da Bandeira'') are actually more recent names given the fortress, named for the area of Lagos on which it is actually located.</ref> This squat rectangular fort guards the entrance to the harbour, accessed by a small [[drawbridge]], to terraced spaces (that overlook the town, beach and harbour) and the small chapel (decorated with 17th-century [[azulejo]]s tile). Until the late 20th century, the fort was used as a service depot for military forces and housed services linked to maritime activities (such as supplies for lifeboats and nautical sports). It was restored between 1958 and 1960, and officially acquired by the municipality of Lagos in 1983, where it was converted into exhibition displays of maritime history, with [[astrolabe]]s and models of caravels.\n* Fort of Pinh\u00e3o ({{lang-pt|Forte do Pinh\u00e3o}})\n* Military Barracks of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio Militar em Lagos/Trem de Artilharia}})\n* Musketeers' Workshop/Warehouse and Saddlery ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio Oficina do Espingardeiro/Armaz\u00e9m do Espingardeiro/Selaria}})\n* Regimental Warehouse/Church of S\u00e3o Br\u00e1s ({{lang-pt|Armaz\u00e9m Regimental e Desparecido Igreja de S\u00e3o Br\u00e1s}})\n* Tower of Atalaia ({{lang-pt|Torre da Atalaia}})\n* Walled/Tower Fortifications of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Muralhas e Torre\u00f5es de Lagos}})\n\n===Religious===\n[[File:Igreja de Santa Maria, Lagos, September 2019.jpg|thumb|Altar area; Igreja de Santa Maria, September 2019]]\n* Chapel/Hermitage of S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o Baptista ({{lang-pt|Capela/Ermida de S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o Baptista}})\n* Church of Nossa Senhora do Carmo ({{lang-pt|Igreja da Nossa Senhora do Carmo}})\n* Church of Nossa Senhora da Luz ({{lang-pt|Igreja da Nossa Senhora da Luz}})\n* Church of Odi\u00e1xere ({{lang-pt|Igreja de Odi\u00e1xere}})\n* Church of Santa Maria ({{lang-pt|Igreja de Santa Maria/da Miseric\u00f3rdia}})\n* Church of Santo Ant\u00f3nio ({{lang-pt|Igreja de Santo Ant\u00f3nio}}) - its simple fa\u00e7ade with the asymmetrical bell towers, date from 1715, and contrast sharply with the extravagantly decorated interior, which is covered in gilded wood carvings and blue-and-white 18th-century [[azulejo]] tiles (''talha dourada'') which fill the walls of the [[nave]], while six [[Baroque]] paintings by Jos\u00e9 Joaquim Rasquinho, representing the miracles of [[Anthony of Padua|Saint Anthony]] are hung on its walls. The wooden [[vault (architecture)|vault]] was painted with a [[trompe l'oeil|trompe-l'oeil]] effect, while polychrome statues of [[cherub]]s playing with animals and fishes are scattered within the interior. It was one of the few buildings to survive the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake|Great Earthquake of 1755]], reconstructed by the local commander of Regimental Infantry, who may have added the polychromatic statue of St. Anthony with military sash. Purportedly, King [[Sebastian of Portugal|Sebastian]] attended his last mass in this church, before his ill-fated expedition to [[Battle of Ksar El Kebir|Morocco]].* Convent of Nossa Senhora do Loreto ({{lang-pt|Convento de Nossa Senhora do Loreto}})\n* Church of S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o ({{lang-pt|Igreja de S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o/de Nossa Senhora da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o}})\n* Hermitage of S\u00e3o Pedro de Pulg\u00e3o/Nossa Senhora dos Aflitos ({{lang-pt|Ermida de S\u00e3o Pedro do Pulg\u00e3o/Nossa Senhora dos Aflitos}})\n* Ruins of the Hermitage of Santo Amaro ({{lang-pt|Ruinas da Ermida de S\u00e3o Amaro}})\n* Ruins of the Convent of the Trinity ({{lang-pt|Ruinas do Antigo Convento da Trinidade/dos Frades Trinos}})\n\n==Culture==\nMany local traditions are celebrated in the municipality and range from gastronomy to traditional handicrafts.\n\nIn gastronomy, there are the local specialties: ''Dom rodrigos'' and ''morgados'' cookies based on local products, such as [[almond]]s, [[ficus|fig]]s and [[egg (food)|eggs]]. Lagos is also a wine-producing region and is famous for its ''[[moscatel]]'' wine, and also for a strong alcoholic spirit,  the ''aguardente de medronho'', made of berries of [[Arbutus unedo|strawberry tree]].\n\n==Notable citizens==\n* S\u00e3o Gon\u00e7alo de Lagos  (c. 1370 - Torres Vedras; 15 October 1422), saint of the [[Order of Saint Augustine]]\n* Soeiro da Costa  (c. 1390 \u2014 c. 1472), navigator and one of the ''Heroic Twelve'' of the ''[[Lusiadas]]''\n* [[Gil Eanes]] (born 15th century - died 15th century), navigator and explorer of the 15th century\n* [[Lan\u00e7arote de Freitas]] (born 15th century - died 15th century), navigator and merchant during the 15th century\n* [[Diogo Rodrigues]] (c.1501; Lagos, Portugal - \u202021 April 1577; Colv\u00e1, Goa), navigator, Captain, Governor.\n* J\u00falia Barroso (11  August 1930 - Lisboa; 23 December 1996) actress, singer and teacher\n* [[J\u00falio Dantas]]  (19 May 1876 \u2014 Lisboa; 25 May 1962), doctor, poet, journalist, screenwriter, politician and diplomat\n* Jos\u00e9 Reis, first [[Portugal|Portuguese]] geriatric physician, who founded the Portuguese Geriatric and Gerontological Society in 1951<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spgg.com.pt/Article/View?ID=126 |title=Breve historial da sociedade Portuguesa de geriatria e gerontologia |work=Sociedade Portuguesa de Geriatria e Gerontologia |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811084534/http://spgg.com.pt/Article/View?ID=126 |archivedate=11 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Portugal}}\n* [[Lagos DOC]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n;Sources\n*{{citation |url=http://www.visitportugal.com/pturismo/Downloads/getFile.aspx?file={D7DBD116-127A-4127-8E8D-39A9A8C0B663}&lang=pt&type=Brochuras&ext=.pdf |title=Taste the Difference |publisher=Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Turismo do Algarve |location=Faro, Portugal |accessdate=24 August 2011 |year=2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928091035/http://www.visitportugal.com/pturismo/Downloads/getFile.aspx?file=%7BD7DBD116-127A-4127-8E8D-39A9A8C0B663%7D&lang=pt&type=Brochuras&ext=.pdf |archivedate=28 September 2011 }}\n*{{citation |first=Rui Mendes |last=Paula|title=Lagos: Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o Urbana e Patrim\u00f3nio |language=Portuguese |location=Lagos, Portugal |publisher=C\u00e2mara Municipal de Lagos |year=1992 |page=392|isbn=978-972-95676-2-9}}\n*{{citation |first=M\u00e1rio |last=Cardo |title=Lagos Cidade: Subs\u00eddios para uma Monografia |language=Portuguese |location=Lagos, Portugal |publisher=Grupo dos Amigos de Lagos |year=1998 |page=80}}\n*{{citation |first=Valdemar |last=Coutingo |title=Lagos e o Mar Atrav\u00e9s dos Tempos |location=Lagos, Portugal |language=Portuguese |publisher=C\u00e2mara Municipal de Lagos |year=2008 |page=95}}\n*{{citation |url=http://www.cm-lagos.pt/NR/rdonlyres/B5C8B347-7463-4C8D-A589-D61