al |issue=14 |year=2000}}\n*{{citation |last=Estevens |first=M. |year=2000 |contribution=Neogene marine mammals inPortugal. Paleogeographical and palcoccological significance. |title=1\u00ba Congresso sobre c Cenozo\u00edco de Portugal|location=Monte de Caparica, Portugal |pages=271\u2013280}}\n*{{citation |last=Antunes |first=M.T. |last2=Jonet |first2=S. |last3=Nascimento |first3=A. |year=1981 |contribution=Vertebres (crocodiliens, poissons) du Miocene marin de I' Algarve occidentale |title=Ci\u00ean\u00e7as da Terra (UNL) |location=Lisbon, Portugal |issue=6 |pages=9\u201338 |language=French}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Lagos, Portugal}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Lagos (Portugal)}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Lagos (Portugal)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110202120921/http://isupportlagos.com/ I Support Lagos: The community web portal of information and news of Lagos, Portugal]\n* [https://medium.com/@mail_60369/good-town-planning-a-lesson-for-politics-c748a1fd2be0 Good Town Planning = Good Politics: Lagos: Positive observations of a planner]\n{{Municipality of Faro District (Algarve)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Faro District]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of the Algarve]]\n[[Category:Towns of the Algarve]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Lagos, Portugal| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Faro District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Portuguese subdivision\n| type            = municipality\n|official_name      = Lagos\n|image_flag         = Pt-lgs1.png\n|image_shield       = LGS.png\n| image_skyline           = {{Photomontage\n| photo1a                 = Vista Centro Hist\u00f3rico de Lagos (cropped).jpg\n| photo2a                 = Igreja de Santo Ant\u00f3nio, Lagos, Portugal 2 (cropped).jpg\n| photo2b                 = Algarve Bucht Lagos (27637090891).jpg\n| photo2c                 = Lagos (41611145272).jpg\n| photo3a                 = Lagos fortress pic 01.jpg\n| photo3b                 = Lagos (40939860814).jpg\n| spacing                 = 2\n| position                = center\n| color_border            = white\n| color                   = white\n| size                    = 280\n| foot_montage            =\n}}\n|image_location     = LocalLagos.svg\n|region             = [[Algarve]]\n|CIM                = [[Algarve]]\n|district           = [[Faro District|Faro]]\n|parishes           = [[#Human geography|4]]\n|leader_name        = Joaquina Matos\n|leader_party       = [[Socialist Party (Portugal)|PS]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|37|6|10|N|8|40|22|W|type:adm1st_region:PT_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = \n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = 212.99\n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 31,049\n|patron             = \n|postal_code        = 8600\n|area_code          = 282\n|website            = http://www.cm-lagos.pt\n}}\n'''Lagos''' ({{IPA-pt|\u02c8la\u0263u\u0283|-|Pt-pt Lagos FF.ogg}}; literally \"lakes\"; {{lang-cel-x-proto|Lacobriga}}) is a municipality at the mouth of [[Bensafrim River]] and along the [[Atlantic Ocean]], in the Barlavento region of the [[Algarve]], in southern [[Portugal]].<ref>Detail Regional Map, Algarve-Southern Portugal, {{ISBN|3-8297-6235-6}}</ref> The population in 2011 was 31,049,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0|title=Statistics Portugal|website=www.ine.pt|accessdate=28 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115205227/http://www.ine.pt/xportal/xmain?xlang=en&xpid=INE&xpgid=ine_indicadores&indOcorrCod=0005889&contexto=pi&selTab=tab0|archivedate=15 November 2016}}</ref> in an area of 212.99&nbsp;km\u00b2.<ref name=dgt>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |title=\u00c1reas das freguesias, concelhos, distritos e pa\u00eds |access-date=2018-11-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105172426/http://www.dgterritorio.pt/cartografia_e_geodesia/cartografia/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal_caop_/caop__download_/carta_administrativa_oficial_de_portugal___versao_2017__em_vigor_/ |archive-date=2018-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The main town of Lagos (which includes only the parish of S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o e Santa Maria) has a population of approximately 22,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ine.pt/scripts/flex_v10/Main.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-22 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109155045/http://www.ine.pt/scripts/flex_v10/Main.html |archivedate=2013-11-09 }}</ref> Typically, these numbers increase during the summer months, with the influx of visiting tourists and seasonal residents. While the majority of the population lives along the coast and works in tourism and services, the inland region is sparsely inhabited, with the majority of the people working in agriculture and forestry.\n\nLagos is one of the most visited cities in the Algarve and Portugal, due to its variety of tourist-friendly beaches, rock formations ([[Ponta da Piedade]]), bars, restaurants and hotels, renowned for its vibrant summer nightlife and parties.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} Yet, Lagos is also a historic centre of the Portuguese [[Portuguese Discoveries|Age of Discovery]], frequent home of [[Henry the Navigator]], historical shipyard and, at one time, centre of the European slave trade.<ref>{{cite book |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=Ziv7J90u-mAC |page=14 }} |title=A Long and Uncertain Journey: The 27,000 Mile Voyage of Vasco Da Gama - Joan E. Goodman, Tom McNeely |publisher= |date= |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref> In 2012, travel website [[TripAdvisor]], classified Lagos as the number one travel destination, on a list of \"15 destinations on the rise\" worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tripadvisor.com/InfoCenter-a_ctr.ontherise__5F__world__5F__en |title=15 destinations on the rise |publisher=Tripadvisor.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lagos43 kopie.jpg|thumb|left|235px|A painting from the 16th century showing a caravel being provisioned in the port of Lagos depicting Africans and Europeans]]\n[[File:Caravela Boa Esperan\u00e7a - Lagos.JPG|thumb|left|235px|Replica of the caravel Boa Esperan\u00e7a]]\n[[File:Mercado de Escravos.jpg|thumb|left|235px|Lagos's slave market. Built in 1444, it was colonial Europe's first slave market]]\nLagos is an ancient maritime town with more than 2000 years of history. The name ''Lagos'' comes from a [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] settlement, derived from the Latin ''[[Lacobriga]]'', the name of the settlement was established during the pre-[[Punics|Punic]] civilizations. It became an early settlement of the [[Carthage|Carthaginians]], who recruited Celtic tribesmen in their war against the Romans (the [[Punic Wars]]). Owing to its already important harbour, it was colonized by the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] and integrated into the Roman province of [[Lusitania]], becoming known as Lacobriga. [[Quintus Sertorius]], a rebellious Roman general, helped by the Lusitanians of Lacobriga (who had been oppressed under Roman Generals and members of [[Lucius Cornelius Sulla]] party), successfully defeated the Roman army of [[Quintus Caecilius Metellus Pius|Caecilius Metellus Pius]] probably at nearby [[Monte Moli\u00e3o]].\n\nWith the fall of Rome, the town of Lagos was occupied in the 6th century by the [[Visigoths]] from the [[Visigoths#Kingdom of Toledo|Kingdom of Toledo]] and later by the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]].\n\nThe [[Moors]] arrived in the 8th century from North Africa, renaming the settlement ''Zawaia'' (meaning ''lago'', or ''lake'').  It became part of the much larger coastal region of ''al-Gharb'', which eventually became known as the ''algarve''. The Moors fortified the town  with [[Lagos Castle]] and established important trade links to Northern Africa from their bases in the Iberian peninsula. In 1174, the local [[W\u0101li]] gave permission for the Christian peoples to construct a church dedicated to S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o Baptista, which was built outside the town's walls (becoming the oldest church in the Algarve).\n\n===Kingdom===\nEven as King [[Afonso Henriques]] advanced to the south, the Christian [[Reconquista]] never made it into Algarve and Alentejo, and remained under Moorish control. King [[Sancho I of Portugal|Sancho I]], with the support of Crusader forces used Lagos as a stepping stone to attack the fortress of Alv\u00f4r.<ref>\nCUP (1970), p.95</ref> Zawaia was eventually captured by King [[Afonso III of Portugal]] in 1241, but was only taken definitively in 1249. From this period on the King began self-styling himself as the ''\"King of Portugal and the Algarve\"'', stressing the fact that the Algarve (which had for so long been ruled by the Moors as a foreign country) had been annexed into the dominion of the Portuguese.\nLagos became an independent jurisdiction under the rule of King [[Peter I of Portugal|Peter I]] in 1361.\n\nKing [[John I of Portugal|John I]] assembled his fleet in the harbour of Lagos, before setting sail for the siege and [[Conquest of Ceuta|conquest of the city of Ceuta]] in 1415. This was the first step in opening the Muslim world to medieval Europe, which in fact led to the [[Age of Discovery]] with Portuguese explorers sailing across the whole world. By the 15th century, Lagos became the centre of Portuguese maritime exploration, with ships ordered south to trace the shoreline of Africa in order to find routes to India. [[Infante]] [[Henry the Navigator]], third son of King John, lived most of the time in Lagos. From here he directed expeditions to [[Morocco]] and to the western coast of [[Africa]] with [[caravel]]s, [[lateen]]-rigged ships with excellent seafaring capabilities. Lagos was also the home port for [[Gil Eanes]] who was the first to sail beyond [[Cape Bojador]] in 1434, after a failed attempt in 1433 that put him out of favour with the, then considered the end of the world. The act of rounding the Cape, much like the later rounding of the [[Cape of Good Hope]], permitted Eanes (and the navigators that followed) to advance into the African subcontinent. When, by 1443, Lan\u00e7arote (then fiscal officer of the crown) had sailed as far as [[Arguim]] and brought back 275 Africans, the Portuguese had sufficient slaves to relieve the perpetual handicap of agricultural labour.<ref>CUP (1970), p.190</ref>\n\nOver the following decades, news of discoveries and achievements, and ships loaded with spices and goods would flow into the port of Lagos.  It was also the gateway for the first African [[slave]]s into post-medieval Europe.<ref name=\"H. Morse Stephens 1891, p.149\">H. Morse Stephens (1891), p.149</ref> Even before Africa was opened-up to the Portuguese, the seamen of Lagos were already enthusiastic slave-catchers.<ref>David Birmingham (2003), p. 27</ref> From the first slave markets in Lagos (the ''Mercado de Escravos'', which opened in 1444), many Africans were dispersed throughout Europe, bringing a considerable income to the Portuguese monarchy and merchant classes, as well as cheap labour force.<ref name=\"H. Morse Stephens 1891, p.149\"/> As the major sponsor of these expeditions, Prince Henry received one-fifth of the selling price of every slave. The demand for the indentured labour force was so high that, by 1450, profit on [[Mauritania]]n slaves was 700 percent.<ref>David Birmingham (2003), p. 29</ref>  The discovery of gold by Alfonso Gon\u00e7ales also increased activities in Lagos, whose residents petitioned the Infante Henry to establish a trading company to pursue gold deposits in the region.<ref name=\"Kerr1\">Robert Kerr (1844), p.189</ref> This included Juan Dias (ancestor of [[Bartolomeu Dias]] who rounded the Cape of Good Hope), [[Gil Eanes]], [[Lan\u00e7arote de Freitas]], Estevan Alfonso and Rodrigo Alvarez, who provisioned a squadron of six caravels to travel to isle of Gar\u00e7as in 1444, but returned with 150 Africans.<ref name=Kerr1/>\n[[File:Centro_de_Lagos.png|thumb|235px|right|The historic centre of Lagos]]\nFollowing the death of Prince Henry, and the expansion into the Atlantic and New World, the port of Lagos continued to receive shipments of goods and slaves, but its role began to decrease. Lisbon, began to prosper, with ships returning directly from the colonies of the Azores, Madeira and Brazil, while trading houses began to relocate to the capital. But, even as the wealth arrived in Lisbon and Lagos, the ostentation was widely on display in the royal residences.<ref>David Birmingham (2003), p. 30</ref>\n\nKing [[Sebastian of Portugal|Sebastian]], obsessed with his plans for a great crusade against the [[Kingdom of Fez]], assembled a huge fleet in Lagos in 1578.<ref>H. Morse Stephens (1891), p.253</ref> During this ill-fated attempt he and most of Portugal's nobility were killed in the [[Battle of Ksar El Kebir]] in Morocco, eventually causing a [[1580 Portuguese succession crisis|succession crisis]], that eventually resulted in the [[Iberian Union]].\n\nWhen Portugal came under Spanish rule, the Portuguese coast became a target for the English fleet.  Lagos, close to the Spanish naval base of [[C\u00e1diz]], was attacked by Sir [[Francis Drake]] in the late 1580s, but was defended by its inhabitants, resulting in Drakes sack of [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]].<ref>CUP (1970), p.275</ref> But, the coast was under regular attack of other [[pirate]]s and [[Privateer|corsairs]], in addition to the Spanish who bombarded the Algarve during the [[Portuguese Restoration War]] (1640\u20131668), which led to the construction of a string of forts all along the coast. One of them was the late-17th-century ''Ponta da Bandeira Fort'' in Lagos, which was completed between 1679 and 1690 (according to the stone inscription over the main door).\n\nFrom 1576 to 1755, Lagos was a high-profile capital of the Algarve, until the old Portuguese town was destroyed by the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake|earthquake and tsunami of 1755]]. Although some walls from the 16th century still remain, as well as the governor's [[castle]], many of the buildings are from the 17th century.\n\nTwo well-known naval battles took place off Lagos, reflecting its strategic location: in the [[Battle of Lagos (1693)]] a French flotilla defeated a combined Anglo-Dutch force, while in the [[Battle of Lagos (1759)]] a British force defeated a French force.\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Dona Ana beach, Lagos.jpg|thumb|right|235px|''Dona Ana Beach (Praia Dona Ana)'']]\n[[File:Praia_do_Pinh\u00e3o.JPG|thumb|left|150px|Pinh\u00e3o beach]]\n[[File:Praia do Porto de M\u00f3s.jpg|thumb|235px|right|Porto de M\u00f3s beach (Praia do Porto de M\u00f3s) is one of the most popular beaches in Lagos, along with Dona Ana and Meia Praia]]\n\n===Physical geography===\nBy its geographical position (east-northeast to west-southwest orientation) and lithological diversity, the Algarve stands out as a unique [[stratigraphy|stratigraphic]] and [[Morphotectonics|morpho-tectonic]] region.<ref name=\"Episodes\">M. Cach\u00e3o, P. Terrinha, A. Santos (2005), p.179-180</ref> A peripheral [[Carboniferous]] unit of the [[Variscan orogeny]], it constitutes the [[Mesozoic]] and [[Cenozoic]] sedimentary layers, deposited onto two totally distinct superimposed basins.<ref name=Episodes/> Between the Middle-Upper [[Triassic]] to [[Hettangian]], sediments evolved from continental ([[fluvial]] red [[sandstone]]) to shallow marine over the entire region, which included instances of evaporates, tholeiite fissural [[magma]]s, lava flows, [[volcanic ash]] and [[pyroclast]]s.<ref name=Episodes/>\n\nThe area of Lagos, conforms to the Middle [[Miocene]] Lagos-Portim\u00e3o formation (a band that extends along the coast from Lagos to [[Albufeira Municipality|Albufeira]], abutting the Serra do Caldeir\u00e3o to the north) and which corresponds to marine sedimentation over relatively stable, but a minorly deformed limestone shelf platform.<ref name=Episodes/><ref name=\"Forst\">Markus H. Forst, Thomas C. Brachert and Joiio Pais (2000), p.290</ref><ref name=\"JPais\">J. Pais et al. (2000), p.279</ref> A period of calm during the intra-Miocene (of approximately 2.4 Ma) led to generalized exposure and development of [[karst]], that influences the present day coastline.<ref name=Episodes/><ref name=JPais/> The conspicuous horizontal bending of this profile in the cliffs of Lagos, much like the remainder of the Lagos-Portim\u00e3o formation, is formed by alternating bands of [[siliciclastic]] and [[calcareous]] [[lithology|lithologies]].<ref name=Forst/> The low degree of cementation in the layers causes a high degree of instability of the cliffs.<ref name=Forst/> The littoral and cliff sands are dominated by various [[bivalvia|bivalve]] organisms, [[bryozoa]]ns, larger [[Benthic zone|benthic]] [[Foraminifera|foraminifers]] and [[Coralline algae]]with minor additions of [[Sea urchin|echinoids]] and [[Balanidae|balanids]] implying a shallow-water depositional system of a warm-temperate climatic regime.<ref name=Forst/> The locality of Cerro das M\u00f3s, from where a large [[Crocodile|crocodilian]] (''[[False gharial|Tomistoma schlegelii]]'') tooth was collected long ago,<ref>M.T. Antunes et al. (1981), p.9-38</ref> has also produced some [[Toothed whale|Odontoceti]] teeth. These may be dated from the [[Serravallian]], which, constitute the oldest marine mammal occurrence in Algarve.<ref name=JPais/><ref>M. Estevens (2000), p.271-280</ref>\n\n===Climate===\n{{Weather box|location = Lagos, Portugal\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n\n|Jan high C = 15.0\n|Feb high C = 16.1\n|Mar high C = 17.8\n|Apr high C = 20.0\n|May high C = 22.2\n|Jun high C = 25.0\n|Jul high C = 27.8\n|Aug high C = 27.8\n|Sep high C = 26.1\n|Oct high C = 22.2\n|Nov high C = 18.9\n|Dec high C = 16.1\n\n|Jan mean C = 10.6\n|Feb mean C = 13.3\n|Mar mean C = 14.4\n|Apr mean C = 16.7\n|May mean C = 18.3\n|Jun mean C = 21.7\n|Jul mean C = 23.9\n|Aug mean C = 23.9\n|Sep mean C = 22.8\n|Oct mean C = 19.4\n|Nov mean C = 16.1\n|Dec mean C = 13.3\n\n|Jan low C = 6.1\n|Feb low C = 10.0\n|Mar low C = 11.1\n|Apr low C = 12.8\n|May low C = 13.9\n|Jun low C = 17.8\n|Jul low C = 20.0\n|Aug low C = 20.0\n|Sep low C = 18.9\n|Oct low C = 16.1\n|Nov low C = 12.8\n|Dec low C = 10.0\n\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 100\n|Feb precipitation mm = 77\n|Mar precipitation mm = 57\n|Apr precipitation mm = 45\n|May precipitation mm = 30\n|Jun precipitation mm = 16\n|Jul precipitation mm = 2\n|Aug precipitation mm = 2\n|Sep precipitation mm = 16\n|Oct precipitation mm = 58\n|Nov precipitation mm = 90\n|Dec precipitation mm = 102\n\n|source 1 = Weatherbase<ref name=Weatherbase>{{cite web\n|url =http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=592905&cityname=Lagos-Faro |title =Weatherbase: Historical Weather for Lagos, Portugal|publisher=Weatherbase|year=2011}}\nRetrieved on November 24, 2011.\n</ref>|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Ecoregions/Protected areas===\nLagos has many natural interest sites, including:\n* ''Ponta da Piedade'' ({{lang-en|Mercy Point}})\n* ''Grutas da Costa d'Oiro'' ({{lang-en|Golden Coast Grottos}})\n* ''Laguna de Alvor'' ({{lang-en|Lagoon of Alvor}})\n*\"Bravura Dam\" {{lang-en|Bravura Dam}})\n* ''Mata Nacional de Bar\u00e3o de S.Jo\u00e3o'' ({{lang-en|National Forest of the Baron of Saint John}}), representing a varied flora that includes Pine (''[[Pinaceae]]''), Acacia (''[[Acacia]]''), Eucalyptus (''[[Eucalyptus]]'') and Strawberry trees (''[[Arbutus unedo]]''), with six pedestrian trails and six campsites. In the zone of Pedra Branca, is a [[Paleolithic]] [[menhir]], called the Menhir of Pedro do Galo, accessible through the pedestrian trails, visitors can use the tables and picnicking areas near the guardhouse for barbecues, while small children have access to a playground. A public sports field and 100 metre interval obstacle course was also constructed to attract activity, near the picnic area.\n\n{{wide image|Bravura_Dam_-_Lagos,_Portugal.png|850px|The Bravura Dam, in the parish of Bensafrim}}\n\n====Beaches====\n[[File:Vista de Lagos.JPG|thumb|right|235px|A view of Lagos and the Meia Praia beach in the background]]\n* ''Meia Praia'' (''Half Beach'') \u2014the most popular tourist beach, consisting of soft, white sand, Meia Praia is one of the largest open bays in Europe, resulting in calm seas, permitting conditions for many nautical sports, while cliffs provide sheltered coves from strong windy conditions;\n* ''Praia Solaria'' (''Sunny Beach'');\n* ''Praia da Batata'' (''Potato Beach'') \u2014 a small beach tucked between two small cliffs (where the river meets the Atlantic Ocean), it is known for the small music festivals that take place there during summer;\n* ''Praia dos Estudantes'' (''Students' Beach'');\n* ''Praia da Dona Ana'' (''[[Don (honorific)|Dona]] Ana Beach'') -its areal is slightly thicker than the beaches in the surrounding area and it is surrounded by striking rock formations. At high tide the beach is split by the geomorphology of the cliffs;\n* ''Praia do Canavial'' (''Canavial Beach'');\n* ''Praia de Camilo'' (''Camilo Beach'');\n* ''Praia da Luz'' (''Beach of Light'') - located in the parish of [[Praia da Luz|Luz]], the beach is bounded in the east by ''Rocha Negra'' ({{lang-en|Black Rock}}), providing summer vactioners with a popular escape during the summer.\n* ''Praia da Balan\u00e7a''- located after ''Praia da Boneca'' and ''Praia dos Pinheiros'', it's a sandy cove enclosed by towering cliffs.<ref name=\"Seabookings\">{{cite web |title=Watersports and boat tours in Lagos |url=https://www.seabookings.com/destination/portugal/35-lagos |website=Seabookings }}</ref>\n\n==Sustainable tourism==\nIn 2012 Lagos received the QualityCoast Gold Award for its efforts to become a sustainable tourism destination. Because of this award, Lagos has been selected for inclusion in the global atlas for sustainable tourism [[DestiNet]].\n<ref>[http://www.qualitycoast.info/brochure/qc2012.pdf Sustainable Tourism Destination EUCC] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170924112831/http://www.qualitycoast.info/brochure/qc2012.pdf |date=2017-09-24 }}\n</ref>\n\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"20\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right;\"\n|\n{{stack|\n{{Historical populations\n|title = Population of<br>Lagos<br><small>(1801 - 2011)</small>\n| 1801 | 9789\n| 1849 | 11012\n| 1900 | 13937\n| 1930 | 16210\n| 1960 | 17060\n| 1981 | 19700\n| 1991 | 21526\n| 2001 | 25398\n| 2009 | 29298\n| 2011 | 30755\n}}\n}}\n|}\n\n===Human geography===\nThe municipality of Lagos is located approximately {{convert|35|km|0|abbr=off}} east of the [[Cape St. Vincent]] coast, along the southern coast of the Algarve. It is surrounded along its borders by the municipalities of [[Vila do Bispo Municipality|Vila do Bispo]] (to the west), [[Aljezur Municipality|Aljezur]] (to the northwest), [[Monchique Municipality|Monchique]] (to the northeast) and  [[Portim\u00e3o Municipality|Portim\u00e3o]] (to the east).\n\nTo the north of Lagos is the road to [[Silves Municipality, Portugal|Silves]], the first capital of Algarve, [[Monchique (parish)|Monchique]] (spa town/mountain), [[Vila Nova de Milfontes|Milfontes]], a coastal town and port/harbour of the city of [[Sines, Portugal|Sines]], that winds through the scenic protected landscape of the Southwest Natural Park (Costa Sudoeste Alentejana e Vicentina).\n\nAdministratively, the municipality is divided into 4 civil parishes (''[[freguesia (Portugal)|freguesias]]''):<ref>{{cite web|title=Law nr. 11-A/2013, page 552 59|url=http://dre.pt/pdf1sdip/2013/01/01901/0000200147.pdf |accessdate=24 July 2014|author=Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica|language=Portuguese|author-link=Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica }}</ref>\n* [[Bensafrim e Bar\u00e3o de S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o]]\n* Lagos (S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o e Santa Maria)\n* [[Praia da Luz|Luz]] which includes the separate villages of [[Alm\u00e1dena]] and [[Espiche]].\n* Odi\u00e1xere\n\n====Twin towns \u2014 Sister cities====\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Portugal}}\nLagos is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n*{{flagicon|POR}} [[Torres Vedras Municipality|Torres Vedras]], district of [[Lisbon (district)|Lisbon]], Portugal\n*{{flagicon|Azores}} [[Ribeira Grande (Azores)|Ribeira Grande]], island of [[S\u00e3o Miguel Island|S\u00e3o Miguel]], [[Azores]]\n*{{flagicon|CPV}} [[Ribeira Grande de Santiago, Cape Verde (municipality)|Ribeira Grande de Santiago]], island of [[Santiago, Cape Verde|Santiago]], [[Cape Verde]]\n*{{flagicon|ESP}} [[Palos de la Frontera]], autonomous community of [[Andalusia]], [[Spain]]\n*{{flagicon|MAR}} [[Ksar El Kebir]], city in the province of [[Larache]], [[Morocco]]\n*{{flagicon|NLD}} [[Sassenheim]], town in the province of [[South-Holland]], [[Netherlands]]\n\n{{wide image|Lagos_2_copy.jpg|2000px|Panoramic view of Lagos's Avenida dos Descobrimentos}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Lagos's Marina.jpg|thumb|right|235px|Lagos's marina]]\nLagos' economy, like many coastal towns in Portugal, has always been closely linked to the sea, and [[fishing]] has been an important activity since very ancient times. Since 1960, the city has embraced [[tourism]], which has become its most important economic activity. It has beautiful beaches, good climate, the sea, a scenic coastline, and historical patrimony.\n\nThe Marina de Lagos has 460 berths and has become an important centre for long-distance cruisers, and it is also known for its modern drawbridge.\n\nLagos also has numerous cultural and night-life entertainment venues.\n\nLagos Station is the western terminus of the railway line from [[Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio Municipality|Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio]] (via [[Tavira Municipality|Tavira]] and [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]]). The passenger train service is operated by [[Comboios de Portugal]] (CP). Connections are available at Tunes for trains to Lisbon and Porto.\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Menir_da_Cabe\u00e7a_do_Rochedo_-_Lagos_-_10-05-2018.jpg|thumb|235px|right|The obelisk-like [[Menir of Cabe\u00e7a do Rochedo]], representing the Neolithic history of the settlements of Lagos]]\n[[File:Muralha_de_Lagos.jpg|thumb|right|235px|The [[Castle of Lagos|walls]] of the old city of Lagos, that extended around the old quarter encircling the central part of Santa Maria and S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o]]\n[[File:Lagos_a%C3%A9ria.jpg|thumb|235px|right|Aerial view of Lagos]]\n[[File:Igreja de Santo Ant\u00f3nio - Lagos.JPG|190px|right|thumb|The two towers of Santo Ant\u00f3nio's Church, which also has a museum inside]]\n[[File:Train at lagos station Portugal.jpg|thumb|right|235px|Train at lagos station Portugal]]\n\n===Prehistoric===\n* Menhir of Cabe\u00e7o do Rochedo ({{lang-pt|Menir da Cabe\u00e7o do Rocheado}})\n\n===Civic===\n* Barracks of the Guarda Fiscal of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Quartel e Posto da Guarda Fiscal}})\n* Building of the [[Caixa Geral de Dep\u00f3sitos]] ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio da Caixa Geral de Depositos}})\n* Building of the Correios, Tel\u00e9grafos e Telefonos ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio dos Correios, Tel\u00e9grafos e Telefones de Lagos}})\n* Building of the Portagem ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio Antigo da Portagem}})\n* District Courthouse/Palace of Justice ({{lang-pt|Tribunal da Comarca/Pal\u00e1cio da Justi\u00e7a}})\n* District Jailhouse of Lagos/Cultural Centre of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Cadeia Comarc\u00e3 de Lagos/Centro Cultural}})\n* D. Maria Bridge ({{lang-pt|Ponte Dona Maria}})\n* Fonte Coberta Dam ({{lang-pt|Barragem da Fonte Coberta}})\n* Gil Eanes Secondary/Commercial-Industrial School ({{lang-pt|Escola Industrial e Comercial de Lagos/Escola Secund\u00e1ria Gil Eanes}})\n* Hotel Tivolli Lagos ({{lang-pt|Hotel de Lagos}})\n* Municipal Hall of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio dos Pa\u00e7os do Concelho}})\n* Lighthouse of Ponta da Piedade ({{lang-pt|Farol da Ponta da Piedade}})\n* Pillory of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Pelourinho de Lagos}})\n* Regional Museum of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Museu Regional de Lagos}}) - this modest regional museum is located next to the church of Santo Ant\u00f3nio.,<ref>[http://www.casabelamoura.com/downloadcenter/CulturalHeritageAlgarve.pdf Guide to the cultural heritage of the Algarve] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304025700/http://www.casabelamoura.com/downloadcenter/CulturalHeritageAlgarve.pdf |date=2016-03-04 }}, By Turismo of Portugal:Algarve, {{oclc|860570547}}</ref> housing the [[Eclecticism|eclectic]] collection of archaeological finds from prehistory and the [[Neolithic]], in addition to minerals, Roman mosaics, Moorish oil-lamps and pottery.  The [[Ethnography|ethnographic]] section includes exhibits from life in the Algarve, that includes not only residential, but also military artefacts, such as swords, muskets and cannonballs, and the [[foral]] (''[[charter]]'') issued by King [[Manuel I of Portugal|Manuel]] for Lagos. Religious artefacts are also prominent in the displays, that include the sacerdotal vestments worn by the [[canon (priest)|canon]]s who said Holy Mass to King Sebastian (before he left on his ill-fated conquest of Morocco), and a [[diptych]] (dating from the 16th century) with scenes from the [[Annunciation]] and [[Presentation of Jesus at the Temple]].\n* Slave Market/Customshoues of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Mercado de Escravos/Vedoria/Alf\u00e2ndega de Lagos}})\n\n===Military===\n* Bulwark of Alcaria/Freiras ({{lang-pt|Baluarte da Alcaria/das Freiras}})\n* Bulwark of Porta dos Quartos ({{lang-pt|Baluarte da Porta dos Quartos}})\n* Bulwark of Santa Maria/Porta da Vila ({{lang-pt|Baluarte de Santa Maria/da Porta da Vila}})\n* Bulwark of S\u00e3o Francisco/Jogo da Bola ({{lang-pt|Baluarte de S\u00e3o Francisco/do Jogo da Bola}})\n* Castle of Senhora da Luz ({{lang-pt|Castelo da Senhora da Luz}})\n* Fort of Meia Praia ({{lang-pt|Forte da Meia Praia}})\n* Fort of Ponta da Bandeira ({{lang-pt|Forte da Ponta da Bandeira}}) - also known as the '''Forte do Pau da Bandeira''', the '''Forte de Nossa Senhora da Penha de Fran\u00e7a''' or the '''Forte do Registo''', the fort, which guarded the entrance to the harbour, was originally dedicated to the ''Santa Virgem Senhora da Penha de Fran\u00e7a'' (to which it was referred).<ref>''Ponta da Bandeira'' (or ''Pau da Bandeira'') are actually more recent names given the fortress, named for the area of Lagos on which it is actually located.</ref> This squat rectangular fort guards the entrance to the harbour, accessed by a small [[drawbridge]], to terraced spaces (that overlook the town, beach and harbour) and the small chapel (decorated with 17th-century [[azulejo]]s tile). Until the late 20th century, the fort was used as a service depot for military forces and housed services linked to maritime activities (such as supplies for lifeboats and nautical sports). It was restored between 1958 and 1960, and officially acquired by the municipality of Lagos in 1983, where it was converted into exhibition displays of maritime history, with [[astrolabe]]s and models of caravels.\n* Fort of Pinh\u00e3o ({{lang-pt|Forte do Pinh\u00e3o}})\n* Military Barracks of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio Militar em Lagos/Trem de Artilharia}})\n* Musketeers' Workshop/Warehouse and Saddlery ({{lang-pt|Edif\u00edcio Oficina do Espingardeiro/Armaz\u00e9m do Espingardeiro/Selaria}})\n* Regimental Warehouse/Church of S\u00e3o Br\u00e1s ({{lang-pt|Armaz\u00e9m Regimental e Desparecido Igreja de S\u00e3o Br\u00e1s}})\n* Tower of Atalaia ({{lang-pt|Torre da Atalaia}})\n* Walled/Tower Fortifications of Lagos ({{lang-pt|Muralhas e Torre\u00f5es de Lagos}})\n\n===Religious===\n[[File:Igreja de Santa Maria, Lagos, September 2019.jpg|thumb|Altar area; Igreja de Santa Maria, September 2019]]\n* Chapel/Hermitage of S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o Baptista ({{lang-pt|Capela/Ermida de S\u00e3o Jo\u00e3o Baptista}})\n* Church of Nossa Senhora do Carmo ({{lang-pt|Igreja da Nossa Senhora do Carmo}})\n* Church of Nossa Senhora da Luz ({{lang-pt|Igreja da Nossa Senhora da Luz}})\n* Church of Odi\u00e1xere ({{lang-pt|Igreja de Odi\u00e1xere}})\n* Church of Santa Maria ({{lang-pt|Igreja de Santa Maria/da Miseric\u00f3rdia}})\n* Church of Santo Ant\u00f3nio ({{lang-pt|Igreja de Santo Ant\u00f3nio}}) - its simple fa\u00e7ade with the asymmetrical bell towers, date from 1715, and contrast sharply with the extravagantly decorated interior, which is covered in gilded wood carvings and blue-and-white 18th-century [[azulejo]] tiles (''talha dourada'') which fill the walls of the [[nave]], while six [[Baroque]] paintings by Jos\u00e9 Joaquim Rasquinho, representing the miracles of [[Anthony of Padua|Saint Anthony]] are hung on its walls. The wooden [[vault (architecture)|vault]] was painted with a [[trompe l'oeil|trompe-l'oeil]] effect, while polychrome statues of [[cherub]]s playing with animals and fishes are scattered within the interior. It was one of the few buildings to survive the [[1755 Lisbon earthquake|Great Earthquake of 1755]], reconstructed by the local commander of Regimental Infantry, who may have added the polychromatic statue of St. Anthony with military sash. Purportedly, King [[Sebastian of Portugal|Sebastian]] attended his last mass in this church, before his ill-fated expedition to [[Battle of Ksar El Kebir|Morocco]].* Convent of Nossa Senhora do Loreto ({{lang-pt|Convento de Nossa Senhora do Loreto}})\n* Church of S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o ({{lang-pt|Igreja de S\u00e3o Sebasti\u00e3o/de Nossa Senhora da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o}})\n* Hermitage of S\u00e3o Pedro de Pulg\u00e3o/Nossa Senhora dos Aflitos ({{lang-pt|Ermida de S\u00e3o Pedro do Pulg\u00e3o/Nossa Senhora dos Aflitos}})\n* Ruins of the Hermitage of Santo Amaro ({{lang-pt|Ruinas da Ermida de S\u00e3o Amaro}})\n* Ruins of the Convent of the Trinity ({{lang-pt|Ruinas do Antigo Convento da Trinidade/dos Frades Trinos}})\n\n==Culture==\nMany local traditions are celebrated in the municipality and range from gastronomy to traditional handicrafts.\n\nIn gastronomy, there are the local specialties: ''Dom rodrigos'' and ''morgados'' cookies based on local products, such as [[almond]]s, [[ficus|fig]]s and [[egg (food)|eggs]]. Lagos is also a wine-producing region and is famous for its ''[[moscatel]]'' wine, and also for a strong alcoholic spirit,  the ''aguardente de medronho'', made of berries of [[Arbutus unedo|strawberry tree]].\n\n==Notable citizens==\n* S\u00e3o Gon\u00e7alo de Lagos  (c. 1370 - Torres Vedras; 15 October 1422), saint of the [[Order of Saint Augustine]]\n* Soeiro da Costa  (c. 1390 \u2014 c. 1472), navigator and one of the ''Heroic Twelve'' of the ''[[Lusiadas]]''\n* [[Gil Eanes]] (born 15th century - died 15th century), navigator and explorer of the 15th century\n* [[Lan\u00e7arote de Freitas]] (born 15th century - died 15th century), navigator and merchant during the 15th century\n* [[Diogo Rodrigues]] (c.1501; Lagos, Portugal - \u202021 April 1577; Colv\u00e1, Goa), navigator, Captain, Governor.\n* J\u00falia Barroso (11  August 1930 - Lisboa; 23 December 1996) actress, singer and teacher\n* [[J\u00falio Dantas]]  (19 May 1876 \u2014 Lisboa; 25 May 1962), doctor, poet, journalist, screenwriter, politician and diplomat\n* Jos\u00e9 Reis, first [[Portugal|Portuguese]] geriatric physician, who founded the Portuguese Geriatric and Gerontological Society in 1951<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spgg.com.pt/Article/View?ID=126 |title=Breve historial da sociedade Portuguesa de geriatria e gerontologia |work=Sociedade Portuguesa de Geriatria e Gerontologia |accessdate=7 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811084534/http://spgg.com.pt/Article/View?ID=126 |archivedate=11 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Portugal}}\n* [[Lagos DOC]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n;Sources\n*{{citation |url=http://www.visitportugal.com/pturismo/Downloads/getFile.aspx?file={D7DBD116-127A-4127-8E8D-39A9A8C0B663}&lang=pt&type=Brochuras&ext=.pdf |title=Taste the Difference |publisher=Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Turismo do Algarve |location=Faro, Portugal |accessdate=24 August 2011 |year=2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928091035/http://www.visitportugal.com/pturismo/Downloads/getFile.aspx?file=%7BD7DBD116-127A-4127-8E8D-39A9A8C0B663%7D&lang=pt&type=Brochuras&ext=.pdf |archivedate=28 September 2011 }}\n*{{citation |first=Rui Mendes |last=Paula|title=Lagos: Evolu\u00e7\u00e3o Urbana e Patrim\u00f3nio |language=Portuguese |location=Lagos, Portugal |publisher=C\u00e2mara Municipal de Lagos |year=1992 |page=392|isbn=978-972-95676-2-9}}\n*{{citation |first=M\u00e1rio |last=Cardo |title=Lagos Cidade: Subs\u00eddios para uma Monografia |language=Portuguese |location=Lagos, Portugal |publisher=Grupo dos Amigos de Lagos |year=1998 |page=80}}\n*{{citation |first=Valdemar |last=Coutingo |title=Lagos e o Mar Atrav\u00e9s dos Tempos |location=Lagos, Portugal |language=Portuguese |publisher=C\u00e2mara Municipal de Lagos |year=2008 |page=95}}\n*{{citation |url=http://www.cm-lagos.pt/NR/rdonlyres/B5C8B347-7463-4C8D-A589-D616CAEAE7A8/0/3caracterizacao_oferta.pdf |title=Pel-Elabora\u00e7\u00e3o do Plano Estrat\u00e9gico do Munic\u00edpio de Lagos: Caracteriza\u00e7\u00e3o da Oferta Tur\u00edstica |publisher=C\u00e2mara Municipal de Lagos |year=2005 |accessdate=24 August 2011 |language=Portuguese}}\n*{{citation |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=aUI9AAAAYAAJ |page=257 }} |title=A general history and collection of voyages and travels, arranged... |volume=2 |first=Robert |last=Kerr |publisher=William Blackwood |location=Edinburgh, Scotland |year=1844}}\n*{{citation |first=H. Morse |last=Stephens |title=The Story of the Nations: Portugal |publisher=G.P. Puntam's Sons |location=London, England |year=1891 |url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=pGMXn7faSQcC }} }}\n*{{cite book |editor=CUP |url= {{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=fHI3AAAAIAAJ |page=275 }} |title=History of Portugal: Pamphlet Collection |year=1970 |publisher=CUP Archive |isbn=1-00-128780-0}}\n*{{citation |url=http://www.cienciasdaterra.com/index.php/vol/article/viewFile/222/211 |contribution=High-resolution correlation of coastal cliff sections in the Lagos-Portimao Formation (Lower-Middle Miocene, central Algarve, Portugal) |title=Ci\u00ean\u00e7ias da Terra |publisher=Universidade Nova de Lisboa |location=Lisbon, Portugal |issue=14 |year=2000 |pages=289\u2013296 |first=Markus H. |last=Forst |first2=Thomas C.|last2=Brachert |first3=Jo\u00e3o |last3=Pais}}\n*{{citation |first=M. |last=Cach\u00e3o |first2=P. |last2=Terrinha |first3=A. |last3=Santos |contribution=Meso-Cenozoic of the Algarve |pages=179\u2013180 |date=September 2005 |title=Episodes |volume=28 |issue=3|publisher=Universidade de Coimbra |location=Coimbra, Portugal}}\n*{{citation |first=J. |last=Pais |first2=P. |last2=Legoinha |first3=H. |last3=Elderfield |first4=L. |last4=Sousa |first5=M. |last5=Estevens |contribution=The Neogene of Algarve (Portugal) |pages=277\u2013288|title=Ci\u00ean\u00e7ias da Terra |publisher=Universidade Nova de Lisboa |location=Lisbon, Portugal |issue=14 |year=2000}}\n*{{citation |last=Estevens |first=M. |year=2000 |contribution=Neogene marine mammals inPortugal. Paleogeographical and palcoccological significance. |title=1\u00ba Congresso sobre c Cenozo\u00edco de Portugal|location=Monte de Caparica, Portugal |pages=271\u2013280}}\n*{{citation |last=Antunes |first=M.T. |last2=Jonet |first2=S. |last3=Nascimento |first3=A. |year=1981 |contribution=Vertebres (crocodiliens, poissons) du Miocene marin de I' Algarve occidentale |title=Ci\u00ean\u00e7as da Terra (UNL) |location=Lisbon, Portugal |issue=6 |pages=9\u201338 |language=French}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Lagos, Portugal}}\n{{EB1911 poster|Lagos (Portugal)}}\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Lagos (Portugal)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110202120921/http://isupportlagos.com/ I Support Lagos: The community web portal of information and news of Lagos, Portugal]\n* [https://medium.com/@mail_60369/good-town-planning-a-lesson-for-politics-c748a1fd2be0 Good Town Planning = Good Politics: Lagos: Positive observations of a planner]\n{{Municipality of Faro District (Algarve)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Faro District]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of the Algarve]]\n[[Category:Towns of the Algarve]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Lagos, Portugal| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Faro District]]\n", "name_user": "Josu\u00e9 Orf\u00e3o", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClimate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagos,_Portugal"}
{"title_page": "Into the Wild (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2007 film by Sean Penn based on the travels of Christopher McCandless}}\n{{Distinguish|Enter The Wild (2018)|Wild (2014 film)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Into the Wild\n| image          = Into the Wild (2007 film poster).png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Sean Penn]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* Sean Penn\n* [[Art Linson]]\n* [[Bill Pohlad]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = Sean Penn\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Into the Wild (book)|Into the Wild]]''|[[Jon Krakauer]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Emile Hirsch]]\n* [[Marcia Gay Harden]]\n* [[William Hurt]]\n* [[Jena Malone]]\n* [[Catherine Keener]]\n* Brian Dierker\n* [[Vince Vaughn]]\n* [[Kristen Stewart]]\n* [[Hal Holbrook]]<!-- per poster -->\n}}\n| music          = {{plainlist|\n* [[Michael Brook]]\n* [[Kaki King]]\n* [[Eddie Vedder]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Eric Gautier]]\n| editing        = [[Jay Cassidy]]\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paramount Vantage]]<ref name=\"afi\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=55175 |title=Into the Wild |website=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006163619/http://www.afi.com/members//catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=55175 |archive-date=October 6, 2016 |access-date=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n* River Road Entertainment<ref name=afi />\n* Square One C.I.H.<ref name=afi />\n* Linson Film<ref name=afi />\n}}\n| distributor    = Paramount Vantage<ref name=afi />\n| released       = {{Film date|2007|9|21}}\n| runtime        = 148 minutes<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.classification.gov.au/Pages/View.aspx?sid=14NrbDwaZdrDiCjCd7hnpw%253d%253d&ncdctx=nBCwjTuRocdOwbmo3jbgA88bvQESskxeiXYChuULpOvawl70FgPS1XnmvTOWL8oK |title=View Title |website=classification.gov.au}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $20 million<ref name=\"the-numbers\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Into-the-Wild |title=Into the Wild (2007) |website=The-Numbers.com |publisher=Nash Information Services |access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>\n| gross          = $56,822,960<ref name=\"the-numbers\" />\n}}\n\n'''''Into the Wild''''' is a 2007 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[adventure drama film]] written, co-produced, and directed by [[Sean Penn]]. It is an adaptation of [[Into the Wild (book)|the book of the same name]] written by [[Jon Krakauer]] and tells the story of [[Chris McCandless|Christopher McCandless]], a man who hiked across [[North America]] into the Alaskan wilderness in the early 1990s. The film stars [[Emile Hirsch]] as McCandless and [[Marcia Gay Harden]] and [[William Hurt]] as his parents; it also features [[Jena Malone]], [[Catherine Keener]], Brian Dierker, [[Vince Vaughn]], [[Kristen Stewart]], and [[Hal Holbrook]].\n\nThe film premiered during the 2007 [[Rome Film Fest]] and later opened outside [[Fairbanks, Alaska]] on September 21, 2007. It was nominated for two [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globes]] and won the award for Best Original Song: \"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\" by [[Eddie Vedder]]. It was also nominated for two [[Academy Awards]]: Best Editing and Best Supporting Actor for Holbrook.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dwb.adn.com/news/alaska/story/9276769p-9191580c.html |title='Into the Wild' premieres in Fairbanks |date=September 4, 2007 |website=Anchorage Daily News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914025353/http://dwb.adn.com/news/alaska/story/9276769p-9191580c.html |archive-date=September 14, 2008 |access-date=July 17, 2008 |quote=The debut of \"Into the Wild\", a movie directed by Sean Penn about a 24-year-old man who starved to death in the Alaska wilderness, drew a packed house Monday night.}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nIn April 1992, Christopher McCandless arrives in a remote area just north of the [[Denali National Park and Preserve]] in Alaska. Noting McCandless' unpreparedness, the stranger who drops him off gives him a pair of gumboots. McCandless travels into the wilderness and sets up a campsite in an [[Stampede Trail#Bus 142|abandoned city bus]], which he calls \"The Magic Bus.\" At first, McCandless is content with the isolation, the beauty of nature around him, and the thrill of living off the land. He hunts with a .22 caliber rifle, reads books, and keeps a diary of his thoughts as he prepares himself for a new life in the wild.\n\nTwo years earlier, in May 1990, McCandless graduates with high honors from [[Emory University]]. Shortly afterwards, he rejects his conventional life by destroying all of his credit cards and identification documents. He donates nearly all of his savings to [[Oxfam]] and sets out on a cross-country drive in his [[Nissan Sunny#B210 (1973\u20131977)|Datsun 210]] to experience life in the wilderness. McCandless does not tell his parents, Walt and Billie McCandless, or his sister Carine what he is doing or where he is going. He refuses to keep in touch with them after his departure, causing his parents to become increasingly anxious and eventually desperate.\n\nAt [[Lake Mead]], McCandless' car is caught in a flash flood, causing him to abandon it and begin hitchhiking. He burns what remains of his cash and assumes a new name: \"Alexander Supertramp.\" In [[Northern California]], McCandless encounters a [[hippie]] couple named Jan Burres and Rainey. Rainey tells McCandless about his failing relationship with Jan, which McCandless helps rekindle. In September, McCandless arrives in [[Carthage, South Dakota]] and works for a contract harvesting company owned by Wayne Westerberg. He is forced to leave after Westerberg is arrested for [[satellite piracy]].\n\nMcCandless then travels on the [[Colorado River]] and, though told by park rangers that he may not kayak down the river without a license, ignores their warnings and paddles downriver until he eventually arrives in Mexico. There, his kayak is lost in a dust storm, and he crosses back into the United States on foot. Unable to hitch a ride, he travels on freight trains to [[Los Angeles]]. Not long after arriving, however, he starts feeling \"corrupted\" by modern civilization and decides to leave. Later, he is forced to resume hitchhiking, after being beaten by [[Railroad police#United States|railroad police]].\n\nIn December 1991, McCandless arrives at [[Slab City, California|Slab City]], in the [[Imperial Valley]], and encounters Jan and Rainey again. There, he also meets Tracy Tatro, a teenage girl who shows interest in McCandless, but he rejects her because she is underage. After the holidays, McCandless decides to continue heading for Alaska. One month later, camping near [[Salton City, California|Salton City]], McCandless encounters Ron Franz, a retired man who recounts the story of the loss of his family in a car accident while he was serving in the [[United States Army]]. He now occupies his time in a workshop as an amateur leather worker. Franz teaches McCandless the craft of leatherwork, resulting in the making of a belt that details McCandless' travels. After spending two months with Franz, McCandless decides to leave for Alaska, despite this upsetting Franz, who has become quite close to McCandless. On a parting note, Franz gives McCandless his old camping and travel gear, along with the offer to adopt him as his grandchild, but McCandless simply tells him that they should discuss this after he returns from Alaska.\n\nFour months later, at the abandoned bus, life for McCandless becomes harder, and he makes several poor decisions. As his supplies dwindle, he realizes that nature is harsh and uncaring. McCandless concludes that true happiness can be found only when shared with others, and he seeks to return from the wild to his friends and family. However, he finds that the stream he had crossed during the winter has become wide, deep, and violent due to the snow thaw, and he is unable to cross. Saddened, he returns to the bus. In a desperate act, McCandless is forced to gather and eat roots and plants. He confuses similar plants and eats a poisonous one, falling sick as a result. Slowly dying, he continues to document his process of self-realization and imagines what it might have looked like if he had managed to return to his family. He writes a farewell letter to the world and crawls into his sleeping bag to die. \n\nAn epilogue states that two weeks later, his body is found by moose hunters. Shortly afterwards, Carine returns to Virginia with her brother's ashes in her backpack.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:IMG 0632.JPG|thumb|320px|[[Salvation Mountain]] where Chris and Tracy took a walk.]] -->\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Emile Hirsch]] as [[Chris McCandless]] a.k.a. Alexander Supertramp\n* [[Marcia Gay Harden]] as Billie McCandless\n* [[William Hurt]] as Walt McCandless\n* [[Jena Malone]] as Carine McCandless\n* [[Catherine Keener]] as Jan Burres\n* Brian H. Dierker as Rainey\n* [[Hal Holbrook]] as Ron Franz\n* [[Kristen Stewart]] as Tracy Tatro\n* [[Vince Vaughn]] as Wayne Westerberg\n* [[Zach Galifianakis]] as Kevin\n* [[Thure Lindhardt]] as Mads\n* Signe Egholm Olsen as Sonja\n* [[Merritt Wever]] as Lori\n* Jim Gallien as Himself\n* [[Leonard Knight]] as Himself\n* [[R. D. Call]] as [[Railroad police|Bull]]\n* [[Cheryl Francis Harrington|Cheryl Harrington]] as social worker\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nThe scenes of graduation from [[Emory University]] in the film were shot in the fall of 2006 on the front lawn of [[Reed College]]. Some of the graduation scenes were also filmed during the actual Emory University graduation on May 15, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.emorywheel.com/detail.php?n=17018 |title=Remake of \"Nerds\" Film Scrapped |publisher=[[The Emory Wheel]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218230828/http://www.emorywheel.com/detail.php?n=17018 |archive-date=2008-12-18 |access-date=2008-01-29}}</ref> The Alaska scenes depicting the area around the abandoned bus on the [[Stampede Trail]] were filmed {{convert|50|mi|km}} south of where McCandless actually died, in the tiny town of [[Cantwell, Alaska|Cantwell]]. Filming at the actual bus would have been too remote for the technical demands of a movie shoot.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mensjournal.com/feature/M162/M162_TheCultofChrisMcCandless.html |title=The Cult of Chris McCandless |website=[[Men's Journal]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080608142652/http://www.mensjournal.com/feature/M162/M162_TheCultofChrisMcCandless.html |archive-date=June 8, 2008 |access-date=August 2, 2008}}</ref> A replica bus used in the movie is now a tourist attraction at a restaurant in [[Healy, Alaska]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g31007-d1906344-r287190523-49th_State_Brewing_Company-Healy_Denali_National_Park_and_Preserve_Alaska.html |title=See the \"Into the Wild\" replica bus from the movie |publisher=[[Trip Advisor]] |access-date=2015-07-15}}</ref>\n\nBrian Dierker, who plays a major supporting role in the film as Rainey, had no previous acting experience and had gotten involved in the production to be a guide for the rafting scenes. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://azdailysun.com/lifestyles/flagstaff-native-and-grand-canyon-boatman-brian-dierker-played-an/article_488c2e6b-b2b2-51ce-8089-f7523833f562.html}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n=== Critical response===\nThe review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 82% of 194 reviews of the film were positive, resulting in a \"Certified Fresh\" rating. Its consensus read: \"With his sturdy cast and confident direction, Sean Penn has turned a complex work of nonfiction like ''Into the Wild'' into an accessible and poignant character study.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/into_the_wild |title=Into the Wild (Rotten Tomatoes) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=July 9, 2011}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] assigned the film an average score of 73 out of 100 based on 38 reviews from mainstream critics.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/intothewild |title=Into the Wild (2007): Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=December 31, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film four stars out of four and described it as \"spellbinding.\" Ebert wrote that [[Emile Hirsch]] gives a \"hypnotic performance,\" commenting: \"It is great acting, and more than acting.\" Ebert added, \"The movie is so good partly because it means so much, I think, to its writer-director, Sean Penn.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070927/REVIEWS/709270305 |title=Into the Wild  (xhtml) |last=[[Roger Ebert]] |date=September 29, 2007 |website=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |access-date=December 31, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n==== Winnings ====\n{{Div col begin}}\n* '''[[65th Golden Globe Awards]]'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/13/AR2008011303970_2.html |title=The Golden Globe Awards |website=The Washington Post |access-date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n** [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song&nbsp;\u2013 Motion Picture]] (\"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\")\n* '''[[Gotham Awards]]'''\n** [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Feature|Best Feature Film]]\n* '''[[Mill Valley Film Festival]]'''\n** Best Actor ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n* '''[[Palm Springs International Film Festival]]'''\n** Director of the Year Award ([[Sean Penn]])\n** Rising Star Award Actor ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n* '''[[National Board of Review]]'''\n** Breakthrough Performance&nbsp;\u2013 Male ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n* '''[[Rome Film Festival]]'''\n** Jury Award (William Pohlad), ([[Art Linson]]), ([[Sean Penn]])\n* '''[[S\u00e3o Paulo International Film Festival]]'''\n** Best Foreign Language Film ([[Sean Penn]])\n* '''[[Italian Online Movie Awards]]'''\n** Best Motion Picture of the Year\n** Best Motion Picture soundtrack\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==== Nominations ====\n{{Div col begin}}\n* '''[[80th Academy Awards]]'''<ref name=\"nom80aa\">[[80th Academy Awards]]</ref>\n** [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] ([[Hal Holbrook]])\n** [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]] ([[Jay Cassidy]])\n* '''[[65th Golden Globe Awards]]'''<ref name=\"65gg\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/81 |title=Hollywood Foreign Press Association 2008 Golden Globe Awards for the Year Ended December 31, 2007 |date=December 13, 2007 |publisher=Golden Globes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215072618/http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/81 |archive-date=December 15, 2007 |access-date=December 17, 2007}}</ref>\n** Best Original Score&nbsp;\u2013 Motion Picture ([[Michael Brook]], [[Kaki King]], [[Eddie Vedder]])\n* '''[[American Cinema editors awards 2008|American Cinema Editors]]'''\n** Best Edited Feature Film&nbsp;\u2013 Dramatic ([[Jay Cassidy]])\n* '''[[13th Critics' Choice Awards|Broadcast Film Critics Association]]'''\n** Best Film\n** Best Actor ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n** Best Supporting Actor ([[Hal Holbrook]])\n** Best Supporting Actress ([[Catherine Keener]])\n** Best Director ([[Sean Penn]])\n** Best Writer ([[Sean Penn]])\n** Best Song (\"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\")\n* '''[[34th C\u00e9sar Awards]]'''\n** [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Foreign Film|Best Foreign Film]]\n* '''[[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards]]'''\n** Best Picture\n** Best Screenplay&nbsp;\u2013 Adapted ([[Sean Penn]])\n** Best Supporting Actor ([[Hal Holbrook]])\n* '''[[Directors Guild of America Awards]]'''\n** Best Director&nbsp;\u2013 Film ([[Sean Penn]])\n* '''[[Cinema Audio Society Awards 2007|Cinema Audio Society]]'''\n** Outstanding Achievement in Sound Mixing for Motion Pictures\n* '''[[Costume Designers Guild Awards]]'''\n** Excellence in Costume Design for Film&nbsp;\u2013 Contemporary\n* '''[[Film Critics Circle of Australia Awards]]'''\n** Best Foreign Film&nbsp;\u2013 English Language ([[Sean Penn]])\n* '''[[Grammy Awards]]'''\n** Best Song Written for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media (\"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\")\n* '''[[Gotham Awards]]'''\n** [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor|Breakthrough Actor]] ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n* '''[[Satellite Awards]]'''\n** Best Original Song (\"Rise\")\n* '''[[14th Screen Actors Guild Awards|Screen Actors Guild Awards]]'''\n** Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture\n** Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n** Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role ([[Hal Holbrook]])\n** Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role ([[Catherine Keener]])\n* '''[[USC Scripter Award]]'''\n** USC Scripter Award ([[Sean Penn]]) (screenwriter), ([[Jon Krakauer]]) (author)\n* '''[[Writers Guild of America Awards]]'''\n** Best Adapted Screenplay ([[Sean Penn]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==== Top ten lists ====\nThe [[American Film Institute]] listed the film as one of ten AFI Movies of the Year for [[2007 in film|2007]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/film/story/2007/12/17/afi-top-films.html?ref=rss |title=No Country for Old Men, Juno named to AFI's Top 10 of year |date=December 17, 2007 |website=[[CBC News|CBC]] |access-date=December 31, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/tvevents/afiawards07/default.aspx |title=AFI Awards 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605081545/http://www.afi.com/tvevents/afiawards07/default.aspx |archive-date=June 5, 2011 |access-date=2009-01-10}}. [[American Film Institute]]</ref>\n\n[[National Board of Review]] named it one of the Top Ten Films of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbrmp.org/awards/awards.cfm?award=Top%20Ten%20Films |title=Top Ten Films |website=National Board of Review |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040202012640/http://www.nbrmp.org/awards/awards.cfm?award=Top%20Ten%20Films |archive-date=2 February 2004 |access-date=17 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Into the Wild'' also ranks 473rd in [[Empire (magazine)|''Empire'' magazine]]'s 2008 list of the 500 greatest movies of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/5.asp |title=Empire's 500 Greatest Movies Of All Time |website=empireonline.com}}</ref>\n\nThe film appeared on many critics' top ten lists of the best films of 2007.<ref name=\"top10mc07\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml |title=Metacritic: 2007 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |website=[[Metacritic]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102102034/http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml |archive-date=January 2, 2008 |access-date=January 1, 2008}}</ref>\n{{Div col begin}}\n* 1st: [[Ben Lyons]], ''[[The Daily 10]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://uk.eonline.com/photos/gallery.jsp?galleryUUID=360de45f-1c26-41c1-99be-839812e57f83#7513b1e5-e81e-4d55-b83b-7e8b855fdef7 |title=Ben Lyons' Top 10 Films of 2007&nbsp;\u2013 Photo Gallery |website=[[E!]] |access-date=July 23, 2008}}</ref>\n* 2nd: Ann Hornaday, ''[[The Washington Post]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 2nd: Tasha Robinson, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 3rd: [[James Berardinelli]], ReelViews<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 3rd: Kevin Crust, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 3rd: [[Peter Travers]], ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<ref>[[Travers, Peter]], (December 19, 2007) [https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17686508/peter_travers_best_and_worst_movies_of_2007/3 \"Peter Travers' Best and Worst Movies of 2007\"] ''Rolling Stone''. Retrieved December 20, 2007</ref>\n* 4th: [[Kyle Smith]], ''[[New York Post]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 5th: Claudia Puig, ''[[USA Today]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 5th: [[David Germain]], [[Associated Press]]<ref name=\"ap\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/Dec/20071227Go!013.asp |title='No Country for Old Men' earns nod from AP critics |last=David Germain |last2=Christy Lemire |date=December 27, 2007 |website=Associated Press, via [[Columbia Daily Tribune]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20080103000750/http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/Dec/20071227Go!013.asp |archive-date=January 3, 2008 |access-date=December 31, 2007}}</ref>\n* 5th: [[Joe Morgenstern]], ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 6th: Carrie Rickey, ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]''<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 6th: [[Steven Rea]], ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]''<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 7th: [[A.O. Scott]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (tied with ''[[The Diving Bell and the Butterfly (film)|The Diving Bell and the Butterfly]]'')<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 7th: Noel Murray, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 9th: [[Christy Lemire]], [[Associated Press]]<ref name=ap/>\n* 10th: [[Roger Ebert]], ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml |title=Metacritic: 2007 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |website=[[Metacritic]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109184636/http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml |archive-date=January 9, 2008 |access-date=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n=== Box office ===\nIn North America, ''Into the Wild'' initially opened in limited release in four theaters and grossed $212,440, posting a per-theater average of $53,110. For the next several weeks, the film remained in limited release until it expanded to over 600 theaters on October 19, 2007; in its first weekend of wide release, the film grossed just $2.1 million for a per-theater average of $3,249. As of December 25, 2008, the film grossed $18,354,356 domestically and $37,281,398 internationally. In total, the film has grossed $55,635,754 worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=intothewild.htm |title=Into the Wild (2007) |website=Box Office Mojo |access-date=December 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Into the Wild'' was released on March 4, 2008 on standard [[DVD]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000ZN802W |title=Amazon.com: Into the Wild |website=amazon.com}}</ref> Two-Disc Special Collector's Edition DVD,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000ZN8036 |title=Amazon.com: Into the Wild (Two-Disc Special Collector's Edition) |website=amazon.com}}</ref> and standard [[HD DVD]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000ZN803G |title=Amazon.com: Into The Wild [HD DVD] |website=amazon.com}}</ref> The special edition DVD and HD DVD contain two special features entitled ''The Story, The Characters'' and ''The Experience''. The [[Blu-ray Disc]] edition was released in France on July 16, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dvdrama.com/news-26541-preview-into-the-wild-en-dvd-blu-ray.php |title=Cin\u00e9ma et S\u00e9ries TV - MYTF1News |website=MYTF1NEWS}}</ref> The Blu-ray edition for the US was released on December 16, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.highdefdigest.com/news/show/Disc_Announcements/Paramount/Into_the_Wild_Coming_to_Blu-ray/2109 |title='Into the Wild' Coming to Blu-ray |website=highdefdigest.com}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{main|Into the Wild (soundtrack)}}\nThe songs on the soundtrack were performed by [[Eddie Vedder]], lead singer of [[Pearl Jam]], and Jerry Hannan. Vedder won a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for the song \"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\". The score was written and performed by [[Michael Brook]] and [[Kaki King]].  The music at the end of the theatrical trailer is \"Acts of Courage\" by [[X-Ray Dog]], a company that supplies music for many movie trailers. Eddie Vedder said whilst writing the songs on the album \"I spent three days giving him (Sean Penn) colors that I could paint with. Different sounds. It would be pump organ and vocal, or it would be an uptempo song. I just gave him 25 minutes of music, stuff I felt that were colors on the palette. And I really didn't think anything was gonna come out of it. Maybe a little piece or something\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2007/09/14/eddie-vedder-his-solo-soundtrack-work |title=Eddie Vedder on his solo soundtrack work |last=Whitney |first=Pastorek |date=14 September 2007 |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Survival film]], about the film genre, with a list of related films\n* [[The Call of the Wild (2007 film)|''The Call of the Wild'']], a 2007 documentary about McCandless made by [[Ron Lamothe]].\n* [[Vagabond (1985 film)|''Vagabond'' (film)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.intothewild.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|0758758|Into the Wild}}\n* {{AllMovie title|352389|Into the Wild}}\n* {{metacritic film|into-the-wild|Into the Wild}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|into_the_wild|Into the Wild}}\n* {{mojo title|intothewild|Into the Wild}}\n* {{AFI film|55175|Into the Wild}}\n\n{{Sean Penn}}\n{{Jon Krakauer}}\n{{Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Feature}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Into The Wild}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:2000s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s independent films]]\n[[Category:2000s adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:American adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:Docudramas]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Environmental films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Brook]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sean Penn]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1990]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1991]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1992]]\n[[Category:Films set in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Films set in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films set in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films set in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Films set in South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Films set in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Films shot in South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Journalism adapted into films]]\n[[Category:American nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Vantage films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2007 film by Sean Penn based on the travels of Christopher McCandless}}\n{{Distinguish|Enter The Wild (2018)|Wild (2014 film)}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Into the Wild\n| image          = Into the Wild (2007 film poster).png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Sean Penn]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* Sean Penn\n* [[Art Linson]]\n* [[Bill Pohlad]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = Sean Penn\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[Into the Wild (book)|Into the Wild]]''|[[Jon Krakauer]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Emile Hirsch]]\n* [[Marcia Gay Harden]]\n* [[William Hurt]]\n* [[Jena Malone]]\n* [[Catherine Keener]]\n* Brian Dierker\n* [[Vince Vaughn]]\n* [[Kristen Stewart]]\n* [[Hal Holbrook]]<!-- per poster -->\n}}\n| music          = {{plainlist|\n* [[Michael Brook]]\n* [[Kaki King]]\n* [[Eddie Vedder]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Eric Gautier]]\n| editing        = [[Jay Cassidy]]\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paramount Vantage]]<ref name=\"afi\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=55175 |title=Into the Wild |website=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006163619/http://www.afi.com/members//catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=55175 |archive-date=October 6, 2016 |access-date=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n* River Road Entertainment<ref name=afi />\n* Square One C.I.H.<ref name=afi />\n* Linson Film<ref name=afi />\n}}\n| distributor    = Paramount Vantage<ref name=afi />\n| released       = {{Film date|2007|9|21}}\n| runtime        = 148 minutes<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.classification.gov.au/Pages/View.aspx?sid=14NrbDwaZdrDiCjCd7hnpw%253d%253d&ncdctx=nBCwjTuRocdOwbmo3jbgA88bvQESskxeiXYChuULpOvawl70FgPS1XnmvTOWL8oK |title=View Title |website=classification.gov.au}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $20 million<ref name=\"the-numbers\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Into-the-Wild |title=Into the Wild (2007) |website=The-Numbers.com |publisher=Nash Information Services |access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>\n| gross          = $56,822,960<ref name=\"the-numbers\" />\n}}\n\n'''''Into the Wild''''' is a 2007 American [[Biographical film|biographical]] [[adventure drama film]] written, co-produced, and directed by [[Sean Penn]]. It is an adaptation of [[Into the Wild (book)|the book of the same name]] written by [[Jon Krakauer]] and tells the story of [[Chris McCandless|Christopher McCandless]], a man who hiked across [[North America]] into the Alaskan wilderness in the early 1990s. The film stars [[Emile Hirsch]] as McCandless and [[Marcia Gay Harden]] and [[William Hurt]] as his parents; it also features [[Jena Malone]], [[Catherine Keener]], Brian Dierker, [[Vince Vaughn]], [[Kristen Stewart]], and [[Hal Holbrook]].\n\nThe film premiered during the 2007 [[Rome Film Fest]] and later opened outside [[Fairbanks, Alaska]] on September 21, 2007. It was nominated for two [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globes]] and won the award for Best Original Song: \"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\" by [[Eddie Vedder]]. It was also nominated for two [[Academy Awards]]: Best Editing and Best Supporting Actor for Holbrook.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dwb.adn.com/news/alaska/story/9276769p-9191580c.html |title='Into the Wild' premieres in Fairbanks |date=September 4, 2007 |website=Anchorage Daily News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914025353/http://dwb.adn.com/news/alaska/story/9276769p-9191580c.html |archive-date=September 14, 2008 |access-date=July 17, 2008 |quote=The debut of \"Into the Wild\", a movie directed by Sean Penn about a 24-year-old man who starved to death in the Alaska wilderness, drew a packed house Monday night.}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nIn April 1992, Christopher McCandless arrives in a remote area just north of the [[Denali National Park and Preserve]] in Alaska. Noting McCandless' unpreparedness, the stranger who drops him off gives him a pair of gumboots. McCandless travels into the wilderness and sets up a campsite in an [[Stampede Trail#Bus 142|abandoned city bus]], which he calls \"The Magic Bus.\" At first, McCandless is content with the isolation, the beauty of nature around him, and the thrill of living off the land. He hunts with a .22 caliber rifle, reads books, and keeps a diary of his thoughts as he prepares himself for a new life in the wild.\n\nTwo years earlier, in May 1990, McCandless graduates with high honors from [[Emory University]]. Shortly afterwards, he rejects his conventional life by destroying all of his credit cards and identification documents. He donates nearly all of his savings to [[Oxfam]] and sets out on a cross-country drive in his [[Nissan Sunny#B210 (1973\u20131977)|Datsun 210]] to experience life in the wilderness. McCandless does not tell his parents, Walt and Billie McCandless, or his sister Carine what he is doing or where he is going. He refuses to keep in touch with them after his departure, causing his parents to become increasingly anxious and eventually desperate.\n\nAt [[Lake Mead]], McCandless' car is caught in a flash flood, causing him to abandon it and begin hitchhiking. He burns what remains of his cash and assumes a new name: \"Alexander Supertramp.\" In [[Northern California]], McCandless encounters a [[hippie]] couple named Jan Burres and Rainey. Rainey tells McCandless about his failing relationship with Jan, which McCandless helps rekindle. In September, McCandless arrives in [[Carthage, South Dakota]] and works for a contract harvesting company owned by Wayne Westerberg. He is forced to leave after Westerberg is arrested for [[satellite piracy]].\n\nMcCandless then travels on the [[Colorado River]] and, though told by park rangers that he may not kayak down the river without a license, ignores their warnings and paddles downriver until he eventually arrives in Mexico. There, his kayak is lost in a dust storm, and he crosses back into the United States on foot. Unable to hitch a ride, he travels on freight trains to [[Los Angeles]]. Not long after arriving, however, he starts feeling \"corrupted\" by modern civilization and decides to leave. Later, he is forced to resume hitchhiking, after being beaten by [[Railroad police#United States|railroad police]].\n\nIn December 1991, McCandless arrives at [[Slab City, California|Slab City]], in the [[Imperial Valley]], and encounters Jan and Rainey again. There, he also meets Tracy Tatro, a teenage girl who shows interest in McCandless, but he rejects her because she is underage. After the holidays, McCandless decides to continue heading for Alaska. One month later, camping near [[Salton City, California|Salton City]], McCandless encounters Ron Franz, a retired man who recounts the story of the loss of his family in a car accident while he was serving in the [[United States Army]]. He now occupies his time in a workshop as an amateur leather worker. Franz teaches McCandless the craft of leatherwork, resulting in the making of a belt that details McCandless' travels. After spending two months with Franz, McCandless decides to leave for Alaska, despite this upsetting Franz, who has become quite close to McCandless. On a parting note, Franz gives McCandless his old camping and travel gear, along with the offer to adopt him as his grandchild, but McCandless simply tells him that they should discuss this after he returns from Alaska.\n\nFour months later, at the abandoned bus, life for McCandless becomes harder, and he makes several poor decisions. As his supplies dwindle, he realizes that nature is also harsh and uncaring. McCandless concludes that true happiness can only be found when shared with others, and he seeks to return from the wild to his friends and family. However, he finds that the stream he had crossed during the winter has become wide, deep, and violent due to the snow thaw, and he is unable to cross. Saddened, he returns to the bus. In a desperate act, McCandless is forced to gather and eat roots and plants. He confuses similar plants and eats a poisonous one, falling sick as a result. Slowly dying, he continues to document his process of self-realization and imagines what it might have looked like if he had managed to return to his family. He writes a farewell letter to the world and crawls into his sleeping bag to die. \n\nAn epilogue states that two weeks later, his body is found by moose hunters. Shortly afterwards, Carine returns to Virginia with her brother's ashes in her backpack.\n\n== Cast ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:IMG 0632.JPG|thumb|320px|[[Salvation Mountain]] where Chris and Tracy took a walk.]] -->\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Emile Hirsch]] as [[Chris McCandless]] a.k.a. Alexander Supertramp\n* [[Marcia Gay Harden]] as Billie McCandless\n* [[William Hurt]] as Walt McCandless\n* [[Jena Malone]] as Carine McCandless\n* [[Catherine Keener]] as Jan Burres\n* Brian H. Dierker as Rainey\n* [[Hal Holbrook]] as Ron Franz\n* [[Kristen Stewart]] as Tracy Tatro\n* [[Vince Vaughn]] as Wayne Westerberg\n* [[Zach Galifianakis]] as Kevin\n* [[Thure Lindhardt]] as Mads\n* Signe Egholm Olsen as Sonja\n* [[Merritt Wever]] as Lori\n* Jim Gallien as Himself\n* [[Leonard Knight]] as Himself\n* [[R. D. Call]] as [[Railroad police|Bull]]\n* [[Cheryl Francis Harrington|Cheryl Harrington]] as social worker\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nThe scenes of graduation from [[Emory University]] in the film were shot in the fall of 2006 on the front lawn of [[Reed College]]. Some of the graduation scenes were also filmed during the actual Emory University graduation on May 15, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.emorywheel.com/detail.php?n=17018 |title=Remake of \"Nerds\" Film Scrapped |publisher=[[The Emory Wheel]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081218230828/http://www.emorywheel.com/detail.php?n=17018 |archive-date=2008-12-18 |access-date=2008-01-29}}</ref> The Alaska scenes depicting the area around the abandoned bus on the [[Stampede Trail]] were filmed {{convert|50|mi|km}} south of where McCandless actually died, in the tiny town of [[Cantwell, Alaska|Cantwell]]. Filming at the actual bus would have been too remote for the technical demands of a movie shoot.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mensjournal.com/feature/M162/M162_TheCultofChrisMcCandless.html |title=The Cult of Chris McCandless |website=[[Men's Journal]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080608142652/http://www.mensjournal.com/feature/M162/M162_TheCultofChrisMcCandless.html |archive-date=June 8, 2008 |access-date=August 2, 2008}}</ref> A replica bus used in the movie is now a tourist attraction at a restaurant in [[Healy, Alaska]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tripadvisor.com/ShowUserReviews-g31007-d1906344-r287190523-49th_State_Brewing_Company-Healy_Denali_National_Park_and_Preserve_Alaska.html |title=See the \"Into the Wild\" replica bus from the movie |publisher=[[Trip Advisor]] |access-date=2015-07-15}}</ref>\n\nBrian Dierker, who plays a major supporting role in the film as Rainey, had no previous acting experience and had gotten involved in the production to be a guide for the rafting scenes. <ref>{{Cite web|url= https://azdailysun.com/lifestyles/flagstaff-native-and-grand-canyon-boatman-brian-dierker-played-an/article_488c2e6b-b2b2-51ce-8089-f7523833f562.html}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n=== Critical response===\nThe review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 82% of 194 reviews of the film were positive, resulting in a \"Certified Fresh\" rating. Its consensus read: \"With his sturdy cast and confident direction, Sean Penn has turned a complex work of nonfiction like ''Into the Wild'' into an accessible and poignant character study.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/into_the_wild |title=Into the Wild (Rotten Tomatoes) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=July 9, 2011}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] assigned the film an average score of 73 out of 100 based on 38 reviews from mainstream critics.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/intothewild |title=Into the Wild (2007): Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=December 31, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film four stars out of four and described it as \"spellbinding.\" Ebert wrote that [[Emile Hirsch]] gives a \"hypnotic performance,\" commenting: \"It is great acting, and more than acting.\" Ebert added, \"The movie is so good partly because it means so much, I think, to its writer-director, Sean Penn.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070927/REVIEWS/709270305 |title=Into the Wild  (xhtml) |last=[[Roger Ebert]] |date=September 29, 2007 |website=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |access-date=December 31, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n==== Winnings ====\n{{Div col begin}}\n* '''[[65th Golden Globe Awards]]'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/01/13/AR2008011303970_2.html |title=The Golden Globe Awards |website=The Washington Post |access-date=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n** [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song&nbsp;\u2013 Motion Picture]] (\"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\")\n* '''[[Gotham Awards]]'''\n** [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Feature|Best Feature Film]]\n* '''[[Mill Valley Film Festival]]'''\n** Best Actor ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n* '''[[Palm Springs International Film Festival]]'''\n** Director of the Year Award ([[Sean Penn]])\n** Rising Star Award Actor ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n* '''[[National Board of Review]]'''\n** Breakthrough Performance&nbsp;\u2013 Male ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n* '''[[Rome Film Festival]]'''\n** Jury Award (William Pohlad), ([[Art Linson]]), ([[Sean Penn]])\n* '''[[S\u00e3o Paulo International Film Festival]]'''\n** Best Foreign Language Film ([[Sean Penn]])\n* '''[[Italian Online Movie Awards]]'''\n** Best Motion Picture of the Year\n** Best Motion Picture soundtrack\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==== Nominations ====\n{{Div col begin}}\n* '''[[80th Academy Awards]]'''<ref name=\"nom80aa\">[[80th Academy Awards]]</ref>\n** [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] ([[Hal Holbrook]])\n** [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]] ([[Jay Cassidy]])\n* '''[[65th Golden Globe Awards]]'''<ref name=\"65gg\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/81 |title=Hollywood Foreign Press Association 2008 Golden Globe Awards for the Year Ended December 31, 2007 |date=December 13, 2007 |publisher=Golden Globes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215072618/http://www.goldenglobes.org/news/id/81 |archive-date=December 15, 2007 |access-date=December 17, 2007}}</ref>\n** Best Original Score&nbsp;\u2013 Motion Picture ([[Michael Brook]], [[Kaki King]], [[Eddie Vedder]])\n* '''[[American Cinema editors awards 2008|American Cinema Editors]]'''\n** Best Edited Feature Film&nbsp;\u2013 Dramatic ([[Jay Cassidy]])\n* '''[[13th Critics' Choice Awards|Broadcast Film Critics Association]]'''\n** Best Film\n** Best Actor ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n** Best Supporting Actor ([[Hal Holbrook]])\n** Best Supporting Actress ([[Catherine Keener]])\n** Best Director ([[Sean Penn]])\n** Best Writer ([[Sean Penn]])\n** Best Song (\"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\")\n* '''[[34th C\u00e9sar Awards]]'''\n** [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Foreign Film|Best Foreign Film]]\n* '''[[Chicago Film Critics Association Awards]]'''\n** Best Picture\n** Best Screenplay&nbsp;\u2013 Adapted ([[Sean Penn]])\n** Best Supporting Actor ([[Hal Holbrook]])\n* '''[[Directors Guild of America Awards]]'''\n** Best Director&nbsp;\u2013 Film ([[Sean Penn]])\n* '''[[Cinema Audio Society Awards 2007|Cinema Audio Society]]'''\n** Outstanding Achievement in Sound Mixing for Motion Pictures\n* '''[[Costume Designers Guild Awards]]'''\n** Excellence in Costume Design for Film&nbsp;\u2013 Contemporary\n* '''[[Film Critics Circle of Australia Awards]]'''\n** Best Foreign Film&nbsp;\u2013 English Language ([[Sean Penn]])\n* '''[[Grammy Awards]]'''\n** Best Song Written for Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media (\"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\")\n* '''[[Gotham Awards]]'''\n** [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor|Breakthrough Actor]] ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n* '''[[Satellite Awards]]'''\n** Best Original Song (\"Rise\")\n* '''[[14th Screen Actors Guild Awards|Screen Actors Guild Awards]]'''\n** Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture\n** Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role ([[Emile Hirsch]])\n** Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Supporting Role ([[Hal Holbrook]])\n** Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role ([[Catherine Keener]])\n* '''[[USC Scripter Award]]'''\n** USC Scripter Award ([[Sean Penn]]) (screenwriter), ([[Jon Krakauer]]) (author)\n* '''[[Writers Guild of America Awards]]'''\n** Best Adapted Screenplay ([[Sean Penn]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==== Top ten lists ====\nThe [[American Film Institute]] listed the film as one of ten AFI Movies of the Year for [[2007 in film|2007]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/film/story/2007/12/17/afi-top-films.html?ref=rss |title=No Country for Old Men, Juno named to AFI's Top 10 of year |date=December 17, 2007 |website=[[CBC News|CBC]] |access-date=December 31, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/tvevents/afiawards07/default.aspx |title=AFI Awards 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605081545/http://www.afi.com/tvevents/afiawards07/default.aspx |archive-date=June 5, 2011 |access-date=2009-01-10}}. [[American Film Institute]]</ref>\n\n[[National Board of Review]] named it one of the Top Ten Films of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbrmp.org/awards/awards.cfm?award=Top%20Ten%20Films |title=Top Ten Films |website=National Board of Review |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040202012640/http://www.nbrmp.org/awards/awards.cfm?award=Top%20Ten%20Films |archive-date=2 February 2004 |access-date=17 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Into the Wild'' also ranks 473rd in [[Empire (magazine)|''Empire'' magazine]]'s 2008 list of the 500 greatest movies of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.empireonline.com/500/5.asp |title=Empire's 500 Greatest Movies Of All Time |website=empireonline.com}}</ref>\n\nThe film appeared on many critics' top ten lists of the best films of 2007.<ref name=\"top10mc07\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml |title=Metacritic: 2007 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |website=[[Metacritic]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102102034/http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml |archive-date=January 2, 2008 |access-date=January 1, 2008}}</ref>\n{{Div col begin}}\n* 1st: [[Ben Lyons]], ''[[The Daily 10]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://uk.eonline.com/photos/gallery.jsp?galleryUUID=360de45f-1c26-41c1-99be-839812e57f83#7513b1e5-e81e-4d55-b83b-7e8b855fdef7 |title=Ben Lyons' Top 10 Films of 2007&nbsp;\u2013 Photo Gallery |website=[[E!]] |access-date=July 23, 2008}}</ref>\n* 2nd: Ann Hornaday, ''[[The Washington Post]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 2nd: Tasha Robinson, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 3rd: [[James Berardinelli]], ReelViews<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 3rd: Kevin Crust, ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 3rd: [[Peter Travers]], ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<ref>[[Travers, Peter]], (December 19, 2007) [https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/17686508/peter_travers_best_and_worst_movies_of_2007/3 \"Peter Travers' Best and Worst Movies of 2007\"] ''Rolling Stone''. Retrieved December 20, 2007</ref>\n* 4th: [[Kyle Smith]], ''[[New York Post]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 5th: Claudia Puig, ''[[USA Today]]''<ref name=top10mc07 />\n* 5th: [[David Germain]], [[Associated Press]]<ref name=\"ap\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/Dec/20071227Go!013.asp |title='No Country for Old Men' earns nod from AP critics |last=David Germain |last2=Christy Lemire |date=December 27, 2007 |website=Associated Press, via [[Columbia Daily Tribune]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20080103000750/http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/Dec/20071227Go!013.asp |archive-date=January 3, 2008 |access-date=December 31, 2007}}</ref>\n* 5th: [[Joe Morgenstern]], ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 6th: Carrie Rickey, ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]''<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 6th: [[Steven Rea]], ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]''<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 7th: [[A.O. Scott]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (tied with ''[[The Diving Bell and the Butterfly (film)|The Diving Bell and the Butterfly]]'')<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 7th: Noel Murray, ''[[The A.V. Club]]''<ref name=top10mc07/>\n* 9th: [[Christy Lemire]], [[Associated Press]]<ref name=ap/>\n* 10th: [[Roger Ebert]], ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml |title=Metacritic: 2007 Film Critic Top Ten Lists |website=[[Metacritic]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109184636/http://www.metacritic.com/film/awards/2007/toptens.shtml |archive-date=January 9, 2008 |access-date=November 13, 2011}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n=== Box office ===\nIn North America, ''Into the Wild'' initially opened in limited release, in four theaters and grossed $212,440, posting a per-theater average of $53,110. For the next several weeks, the film remained in limited release until it expanded to over 600 theaters on October 19, 2007; in its first weekend of wide release, the film grossed just $2.1 million for a per-theater average of $3,249. As of December 25, 2008, the film grossed $18,354,356 domestically and $37,281,398 internationally. In total, the film has grossed $55,635,754 worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=intothewild.htm |title=Into the Wild (2007) |website=Box Office Mojo |access-date=December 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Into the Wild'' was released on March 4, 2008 on standard [[DVD]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000ZN802W |title=Amazon.com: Into the Wild |website=amazon.com}}</ref> Two-Disc Special Collector's Edition DVD,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000ZN8036 |title=Amazon.com: Into the Wild (Two-Disc Special Collector's Edition) |website=amazon.com}}</ref> and standard [[HD DVD]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000ZN803G |title=Amazon.com: Into The Wild [HD DVD] |website=amazon.com}}</ref> The special edition DVD and HD DVD contain two special features entitled ''The Story, The Characters'' and ''The Experience''. The [[Blu-ray Disc]] edition was released in France on July 16, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dvdrama.com/news-26541-preview-into-the-wild-en-dvd-blu-ray.php |title=Cin\u00e9ma et S\u00e9ries TV - MYTF1News |website=MYTF1NEWS}}</ref> The Blu-ray edition for the US was released on December 16, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.highdefdigest.com/news/show/Disc_Announcements/Paramount/Into_the_Wild_Coming_to_Blu-ray/2109 |title='Into the Wild' Coming to Blu-ray |website=highdefdigest.com}}</ref>\n\n== Soundtrack ==\n{{main|Into the Wild (soundtrack)}}\nThe songs on the soundtrack were performed by [[Eddie Vedder]], lead singer of [[Pearl Jam]], and Jerry Hannan. Vedder won a [[Golden Globe Award|Golden Globe]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for the song \"[[Guaranteed (Eddie Vedder song)|Guaranteed]]\". The score was written and performed by [[Michael Brook]] and [[Kaki King]].  The music at the end of the theatrical trailer is \"Acts of Courage\" by [[X-Ray Dog]], a company that supplies music for many movie trailers. Eddie Vedder said whilst writing the songs on the album \"I spent three days giving him (Sean Penn) colors that I could paint with. Different sounds. It would be pump organ and vocal, or it would be an uptempo song. I just gave him 25 minutes of music, stuff I felt that were colors on the palette. And I really didn't think anything was gonna come out of it. Maybe a little piece or something\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2007/09/14/eddie-vedder-his-solo-soundtrack-work |title=Eddie Vedder on his solo soundtrack work |last=Whitney |first=Pastorek |date=14 September 2007 |publisher=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Survival film]], about the film genre, with a list of related films\n* [[The Call of the Wild (2007 film)|''The Call of the Wild'']], a 2007 documentary about McCandless made by [[Ron Lamothe]].\n* [[Vagabond (1985 film)|''Vagabond'' (film)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.intothewild.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|0758758|Into the Wild}}\n* {{AllMovie title|352389|Into the Wild}}\n* {{metacritic film|into-the-wild|Into the Wild}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|into_the_wild|Into the Wild}}\n* {{mojo title|intothewild|Into the Wild}}\n* {{AFI film|55175|Into the Wild}}\n\n{{Sean Penn}}\n{{Jon Krakauer}}\n{{Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Feature}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Into The Wild}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:2000s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2000s independent films]]\n[[Category:2000s adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:American adventure drama films]]\n[[Category:Docudramas]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Environmental films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Brook]]\n[[Category:Films based on non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sean Penn]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1990]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1991]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1992]]\n[[Category:Films set in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Films set in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films set in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films set in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Films set in South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Films set in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Alaska]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Arizona]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Films shot in South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Journalism adapted into films]]\n[[Category:American nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Vantage films]]\n", "name_user": "Duanefromri", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Into_the_Wild_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Olli Mennander", "text_new": "'''Olli Adolf Mennander''' (6 June 1936 [[Mikkeli]] - 6 October 2012 [[Helsinki]] <ref name=\"muisto\"/>) was a Finnish diplomat, a Bachelor of Political Science. He was the Finnish Ambassador at the Permanent Representation of [[International organization|International Organizations]] in [[Geneva]] 1986\u20131989, the negotiating official in the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs]] 1989\u20131991, the Ambassador in [[Brussels]] 1991-1996 and [[Bern]] 1996<ref>Facta 2001, T\u00e4ydennysosa 1990, WSOY 1990, s. 361 {{in lang|fi}}</ref><ref>WSOY Iso Tietosanakirja 6. osa, s. 157, WSOY 1996 {{in lang|fi}}</ref>\u20132001 <ref>[http://www.finlandia.ch/public/default.aspx?nodeid=38797&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI Suomen suurl\u00e4hetyst\u00f6 Bern] {{in lang|fi}}</ref> -2001  He was accredited to the [[Holy See]] since 1991.<ref name=\"muisto\">[http://www.hs.fi/muistot/a1364357571800 Muistot. Hs.fi], 13.10.2016 {{in lang|fi}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mennander, Olli}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to West Germany]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to the Holy See]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Belgium]]\n[[Category:People from Mikkeli]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of Finland to the United Nations]]\n", "text_old": "'''Olli Adolf Mennander''' (6 June 1936 [[Mikkeli]] - 6 October 2012 [[Helsinki]] <ref name=\"muisto\"/>) was a Finnish diplomat, a Bachelor of Political Science. He was the Finnish Ambassador at the Permanent Representation of [[International organization|International Organizations]] in [[Geneva]] 1986-1989, the negotiating official in the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs]] 1989-1991, the Ambassador in [[Brussels]] 1991-1996 and [[Bern]] 1996<ref>Facta 2001, T\u00e4ydennysosa 1990, WSOY 1990, s. 361 {{in lang|fi}}</ref><ref>WSOY Iso Tietosanakirja 6. osa, s. 157, WSOY 1996 {{in lang|fi}}</ref>\u20132001 <ref>[http://www.finlandia.ch/public/default.aspx?nodeid=38797&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI Suomen suurl\u00e4hetyst\u00f6 Bern] {{in lang|fi}}</ref> -2001  He was accredited to the [[Holy See]] since 1991.<ref name=\"muisto\">[http://www.hs.fi/muistot/a1364357571800 Muistot. Hs.fi], 13.10.2016 {{in lang|fi}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mennander, Olli}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to West Germany]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to the Holy See]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Belgium]]\n[[Category:People from Mikkeli]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of Finland to the United Nations]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1986-1989 \u2192 1986\u20131989 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olli_Mennander"}
{"title_page": "Bavelile Hlongwa", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Bavelile Hlongwa\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Hlongwa_large.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| order = \n| office = [[Cabinet of South Africa|Deputy Minister of Mineral Resources and Energy]]\n| term_start = 30 May 2019\n| deputy = \n| term_end = 13 September 2019\n| president = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n| predecessor = ''Post created''\n| successor = ''Vacant''\n| order2 = \n| office2 = [[National Assembly (South Africa)|Member of the National Assembly]]\n| term_start2 = 22 May 2019\n| term_end2 = 13 September 2019\n| president2 =\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1981|04|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Umzinto]], South Africa\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|09|13|1981|04|14|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Hammanskraal]], South Africa\n| birthname = Bavelile Gloria Hlongwa\n| nationality = South African\n| party = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty = \n| relations = \n| children = \n| parents = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Bavelile Gloria Hlongwa''' (14 April 1981 \u2013 13 September 2019) was a South African chemical engineer and politician from [[KwaZulu-Natal]] and a party member of the [[African National Congress]] (ANC). She was the [[Cabinet of South Africa|Deputy Minister of Mineral Resources and Energy]] and a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] from May 2019 until her death in September 2019.<ref>[https://www.enca.com/news/deputy-minerals-minister-bavelile-hlongwa-dies-car-crash Deputy Mineral Resources Minister Bavelile Hlongwa dies], Johannesburg, ''eNCA'', 14 September 2019. Retrieved on 14 September 2019.</ref><ref>[https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/accidents/2179129/ramaphosa-shocked-and-saddened-by-deputy-minister-hlongwas-death/ Ramaphosa \u2018shocked and saddened\u2019 by Deputy Minister Hlongwa\u2019s death], ''The Citizen'', 14 September 2019. Retrieved on 14 September 2019.</ref><ref>Somdyala, Kamva. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/deputy-minister-hlongwa-was-assisting-overturned-vehicle-when-she-died-20190914 Deputy minister Hlongwa was assisting overturned vehicle when she died], ''News24'', 14 September 2019. Retrieved on 14 September 2019.</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nBavelile Gloria Hlongwa was born on 4 April 1981 in the town of [[Umzinto]] in the [[KwaZulu-Natal]] province. She began her schooling career at Ncazuka Primary School in 1989 and matriculated from Sihle High School in 2000. She studied at the [[University of KwaZulu-Natal#Howard College campus|University of KwaZulu-Natal Howard College campus]] and achieved a Bachelors of Science Degree in [[Chemical Engineering]]. While at university, Hlongwa became active in the [[ANC Youth League]] and other student organisations. She was pursuing a Master's Degree in [[Public Administration]] at the time of her death.<ref name = \"tsa\">[https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/bavelile-hlongwa-deputy-minister-killed-in-car-crash/ Bavelile Hlongwa: Deputy Minister of minerals and energy dies in car crash], ''The South African'', 14 September 2019. Retrieved on 14 September 2019.</ref><ref name = \"energycoza\">[http://www.energy.gov.za/files/aboutus/Deputy-Minister-Hlongwa-Profile.pdf PROFILE Ms Bavelile Hlongwa], ''www.energy.gov.za''. Retrieved on 14 September 2019.</ref>\n\nHlongwa has held various leadership positions. She was appointed to serve on the Local Community Development Committee in 1999. Hlongwa was elected to the South African Institute of Chemical Engineers in 2011, and, in 2013, she was designated as Treasurer for the structure. She was appointed Executive Deputy Chairperson of the Board of the National Youth Development Agency in 2017.<ref name=\"tsa\" /><ref name=\"energycoza\" />\n\nHlongwa started her career as a chemical engineer at Shell Downstream SA. She worked as an engineer from 2011 to 2013, and soon as a production engineer from 2013 to 2015 at Sapref. She was also a gas scheduler at the company from 2016 to 2017.<ref name=\"energycoza\" />\n\nHlongwa was appointed as the Executive Deputy Chairperson of the Board of the National Youth Development Agency in 2017, while she was Deputy President of Convocation Executive Committee at the [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]]. From 2017 to 2019, she served as a non-executive board member of the Dube Trade Port Corporation. Hlongwa was a non-executive board member of the National Metrology Institute of South Africa from 2018 until 2019.<ref name=\"energycoza\" />\n\n==Political career==\nHlongwa was elected central president of the SRC at [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]] in 2009. She was a member of the [[ANC Youth League]] and worked as a member of the ANCYL's KwaZulu-Natal branch task team and was a member of various subcommittees from 2013 to 2015. She was a critic of the [[ANC Women's League]].<ref name=\"energycoza\" />\n\nIn May 2019, Hlongwa was elected to the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]. She took office as a Member on 22 May 2019. President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] soon after on 29 May 2019 appointed her as Deputy Minister of Mineral Resources and Energy, serving alongside Minister [[Gwede Mantashe]]. She was sworn in on 30 May 2019 and consequently became one of the youngest members of the cabinet.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahlati |first1=Zintle |title=Ramaphosa announces his new Cabinet |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/ramaphosa-announces-his-new-cabinet-23148637 |accessdate=16 September 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=29 May 2019}}</ref><ref>Head, Tom. \n [https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/list-of-cabinet-ministers-south-africa-cyril-ramaphosa/ Ramaphosa announces his Cabinet: Here\u2019s the complete list of ministers], ''The South African'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved on 14 September 2019.</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=JUST IN Cabinet reduced from 36 ministers to 28 - Cyril Ramaphosa |url=https://www.heraldlive.co.za/news/2019-05-29-cabinet-reduced-from-36-ministers-to-28-president-cyril-ramaphosa/ |accessdate=16 September 2019 |agency=HeraldLIVE |date=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nHlongwa died on 13 September 2019, when a truck ploughed into a previous car accident scene she was assisting with. The accident claimed the lives of Hlongwa and three other people. The accident occurred close to Maubane Bridge on the N1 at Carousel Plaza, [[Hammanskraal]]. President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] was saddened to hear about her death and declared that a state funeral would be held for her.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2019/09/15/deputy-minister-hlongwa-to-be-given-state-funeral Deputy minister Hlongwa to be given state funeral], ''EWN''. Retrieved on 16 September 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-09-14-deputy-minister-bavelile-hlongwa-dies-in-car-crash/ Deputy minister Bavelile Hlongwa dies in car crash], ''TimesLIVE'', 14 September 2014. Retrieved on 14 September 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.gov.za/speeches/president-cyril-ramaphosa-untimely-passing-deputy-minister-hlongwa-14-sep-2019-0000 President Cyril Ramaphosa on untimely passing of Deputy Minister Hlongwa], ''South African Government'', 14 September 2019. Retrieved on 14 September 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/deputy-minister-dies-in-car-crash-32949503 Deputy minister dies in car crash]. Retrieved on 14 September 2019.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/pretoria-news/man-involved-in-accident-that-killed-minister-bavelile-hlongwa-gets-r3-000-bail-38488394|title=Man involved in accident that killed minister Bavelile Hlongwa gets R3 000 bail {{!}} Pretoria News|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\nA memorial service for Hlongwa was held on 19 September 2019.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2019/09/20/bavelile-hlongwa-dreamt-of-becoming-anc-president Bavelile Hlongwa dreamed of becoming ANC president, memorial service told]. ''EWN''. Retrieved on 20 September 2019.</ref> The University of KwaZulu-Natal cancelled its memorial service it was scheduled to hold for her.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/kwazulu-natal/ukzn-cancels-memorial-service-for-bavelile-hlongwa-33279793 UKZN cancels memorial service for Bavelile Hlongwa], ''IOL'', 19 September 2019. Retrieved on 21 September 2019.</ref> Hlongwa's funeral was held on 21 September 2019.<ref>Zulu, Sifiso. [https://ewn.co.za/2019/09/21/funeral-of-deputy-minister-hlongwa-to-take-place-today Funeral of Deputy Minister Hlongwa to take place today], ''EWN'', 21 September 2019. Retrieved on 21 September 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/ramaphosa-zuma-pay-homage-to-fallen-deputy-minister-bavelile-hlongwa-33387407 Ramaphosa, Zuma pay homage to fallen deputy minister Bavelile Hlongwa], ''IOL''. Retrieved on 21 September 2019.</ref><ref>Mitchley, Alex. [https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/hlongwa-died-as-she-lived-helping-people-ramaphosa-20190921 Hlongwa died as she lived; helping people - Ramaphosa] ''News24'', 21 September 2019. Retrieved on 21 September 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/bavelile-gloria-hlongwa/#experience Bavelile Gloria Hlongwa \u2013 People's Assembly]\n*[https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/mineral-resources-and-energy-ministry/bavelile-hlongwa-ms Bavelile Hlongwa, Ms \u2013 South African Gpvernment]\n{{Authority control}}{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hlongwa, Bavelile}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in South Africa]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:People from uMdoni Local Municipality]]\n[[Category:People from KwaZulu-Natal]]\n[[Category:South African chemical engineers]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African engineers]]\n[[Category:South African women engineers]]\n[[Category:Women chemical engineers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Bavelile Hlongwa\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| order = \n| office = [[Cabinet of South Africa|Deputy Minister of Mineral Resources and Energy]]\n| term_start = 30 May 2019\n| deputy = \n| term_end = 13 September 2019\n| president = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n| predecessor = ''Post created''\n| successor = ''Vacant''\n| order2 = \n| office2 = [[National Assembly (South Africa)|Member of the National Assembly]]\n| term_start2 = 22 May 2019\n| term_end2 = 13 September 2019\n| president2 =\n| predecessor2 =\n| successor2 =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1981|04|14|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Umzinto]], South Africa\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2019|09|13|1981|04|14|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Hammanskraal]], South Africa\n| birthname = Bavelile Gloria Hlongwa\n| nationality = South African\n| party = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty = \n| relations = \n| children = \n| parents = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of KwaZulu-Natal]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Bavelile Gloria Hlongwa''' (14 April 1981 \u2013 13 September 2019) was a South African chemical engineer and politician from [[KwaZulu-Natal]] and a party member of the [[African National Congress]] (ANC). She was the [[Cabinet of South Africa|Deputy Minister of Mineral Resources and Energy]] and a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]] from May 2019 un