ews|date=March 7, 2002 |accessdate=September 23, 2012}}</ref><ref name=PeopleMagazine>{{cite magazine|last=Brock |first=Pope |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20112311,00.html |title=A Crusader Falls |magazine=People.com |date=March 30, 1992 |accessdate=November 2, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|October 24, 1993}}||[[Assassinations of Little Haiti journalists|Dona St. Plite]]||[[WQVN|WKAT]]||Little Haiti, Miami, Florida||St. Plite was attending a benefit for former colleague Fritz Dor when he was also assassinated for supporting [[Jean-Bertrand Aristide]].<ref name=csmonitoronhaiti>{{cite journal|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1993/1027/27032.html |title=Haiti's Culture of Violence Extends to Miami / The Christian Science Monitor |journal=Christian Science Monitor |date=October 27, 1993 |accessdate=November 16, 2012}}</ref><ref name=sunsentinelstplite>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1993-10-26/news/9310260020_1_st-plite-haitian-commentator-s-death-president-jean-bertrand-aristide |title=Haitian Commentator's Death |publisher=Sun Sentinel |date=October 26, 1993 |accessdate=November 6, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|October 18, 2000}} ||[[James Edwin Richards]]||Citizen journalist, editor and publisher||[[Venice, Los Angeles]], California|| Richards was murdered at his Oakwood neighborhood home in the neighborhood where he had established himself as a citizen crime reporter.<ref name=abcnews>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=95310&page=1#.UFJybrJlRQQ |title=Was an LA Activist Shot for His Anti-Crime Efforts? \u2013 ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |accessdate=October 24, 2013|date=2006-01-07 }}</ref><ref name=death>{{cite news|first1=Gina |last1=Piccalo |first2=Kurt |last2=Streeter |title=Venice Anti-Gang Activist Killed in His Driveway |newspaper=LA Times |date=October 19, 2000 |accessdate=November 8, 2013 |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2000/oct/19/local/me-38801}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|September 11, 2001}}||[[Bill Biggart]]||Freelance photographer||[[Lower Manhattan]], New York City, New York||Killed while photographing the rescue effort outside the World Trade Center before the tower collapsed.<ref>{{cite news | first=Rome |last=Neal | title=Bill Biggart: Final Exposures | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2002/09/05/september11/main520940.shtml |publisher=CBS News |date=September 6, 2002  |accessdate=November 6, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|October 5, 2001}}||[[Robert Stevens (photo editor)|Robert Stevens]]||''[[Sun (supermarket tabloid)|Sun]]''||[[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]], Florida||Murdered as one of the media targets of the [[2001 anthrax attacks]] less than a month after 9/11.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chronology of 2001 anthrax events |url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/local/palmbeach/sfl-1013anthraxchronology,0,4805314.story |publisher=sun-sentinel |date=December 24, 2012 |accessdate=December 26, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|August 2, 2007}}||[[Chauncey Bailey]]||''[[The Oakland Post (California)|The Oakland Post]]''||[[Oakland, California|Oakland]], California||After investigating corruption in his community, Bailey was murdered on his way to work by the target of his reporting.<ref name=peele /><ref name=sfgate2007>{{cite news | author=Christopher Heredia, Leslie Fulbright and Marisa Lagos | title=Hit man kills newspaper editor on Oakland street | url=http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/08/02/BAGGCRBL8A6.DTL&tsp=1  | newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | date=August 2, 2007 |accessdate=November 6, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|{{dts|August 26, 2015}}||[[Murders of Alison Parker and Adam Ward|Alison Parker]]||rowspan=2|[[WDBJ|WDBJ 7]]||rowspan=2|[[Moneta, Virginia|Moneta]], Virginia||rowspan=2|Parker, a reporter, and Ward, a photojournalist, [[Murders of Alison Parker and Adam Ward|were shot on live television]] by one-time colleague Vester Flanagan while interviewing a subject about tourism.<ref name=nytimes2015>{{Cite news|title=2 Virginia TV Crew Members Are Killed During Live Broadcast |newspaper=New York Times |date=August 26, 2015|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/27/us/wdbj7-virginia-journalists-shot-during-live-broadcast.html?hp&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=second-column-region&region=top-news&WT.nav=top-news}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Murders of Alison Parker and Adam Ward|Adam Ward]]\n|-\n|rowspan=4|{{dts|June 28, 2018}}||Gerald Fischman|| rowspan=\"4\" |''[[The Capital]]''||rowspan=4|[[Annapolis, Maryland|Annapolis]], Maryland||rowspan=5|The five employees of ''The Capital'' were murdered during the [[Capital Gazette shooting]] in the newspaper's office. The suspect in the shooting, Jarrod Ramos, had held a grudge against the newspaper since it published a story about his guilty plea in a criminal harassment case in 2011.<ref name=\"BaltSun\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/crime/bs-md-ramos-search-20180628-story.html |title=Sources identify suspect in Annapolis Capital shooting as Jarrod Ramos, who had long-running feud with paper |last=Duncan |first=Ian |date=June 28, 2018 |work=Baltimore Sun |access-date=June 28, 2018 |last2=Bogel-Burroughs |first2=Nicholas |language=en-US}}</ref> Hiassen was an editor and columnist, Fischman was an editorial columnist, Winters was a features journalist. McNamara was a sports reporter for the ''Capital'' and the editor for the affiliated weekly ''Bowie Blade-News''. Also killed in the shooting was Rebecca Smith, a sales associate for Capital Gazette Communications.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Marbella |first1=Jean |title=Capital Gazette editor Rob Hiaasen identified as victim of shooting at newspaper |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-rob-hiaasen-20180628-story.html |website=baltimoresun.com |accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wenger |first1=Yvonne |title=Capital Gazette shooting victim Wendi Winters: A prolific writer who chronicled her community |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-wendi-winters-20180628-story.html |website=baltimoresun.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Erin |title=Capital Gazette shooting victim Gerald Fischman: Clever and quirky voice of a community newspaper |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-gerald-fischman-20180628-story.html |website=baltimoresun.com |accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=McDaniels |first1=Andrea K. |title=Capital Gazette shooting victim John McNamara: Sports reporting was his dream job |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-john-mcnamara-20180628-story.html |website=baltimoresun.com |accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Jessica |title=Capital Gazette shooting victim Rebecca Smith: Recent hire loved spending time with family |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/anne-arundel/bs-md-ar-rebecca-smith-20180628-story.html |website=baltimoresun.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Rob Hiaasen]]\n|-\n| [[John McNamara, sportswriter|John McNamara]]\n|-\n| Wendi Winters\n|}\n\n==Other journalists and media workers killed on 9/11==\nThe only professional, working journalist to die while covering the September 11 terrorist attacks on the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] in New York City was photojournalist [[Bill Biggart]], who was killed by falling debris as he was taking photographs.<ref name=irish>{{cite news|first=Conor |last=O'Clery |newspaper=The Irish Times |title=The parting shot |date=December 22, 2001 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2001/1222/01122200163.html}}</ref><ref name=Newsweek>{{cite magazine|first=Jerry |last=Adler |title=Shooting To the End |magazine=Newsweek |date=October 15, 2001 |accessdate=February 28, 2013 |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2001/10/14/shooting-to-the-end.html}}</ref> However, the [[International Federation of Journalists]], which also counts media workers, said that six other media workers and a journalist who were not working at the time died in the attacks. Among those media workers [[Bill Biggart#Context|listed]] as killed were six broadcast TV engineers, who worked inside a tower, and another professional photojournalist, who was a passenger on the first plane that was flown into the WTC.<ref name=CBS2001>{{cite news|title=100 Journalists Killed In 2001 |publisher=CBS News |date=February 11, 2009 |accessdate=March 1, 2011 |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-202_162-321563.html}}</ref>\n\n* Rod Coppola, TV engineer for [[WNET|WNET-TV]], WTC (North Tower)<ref name=ifex2001>{{cite news |title=At Pakistan/Afghanistan Border; Journalist Among Dead and Media Workers Missing |publisher=IFEX.org |date=September 25, 2001 |url=http://www.ifex.org/2001/09/25/at_pakistan_afghanistan_border/ |access-date=March 6, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912072321/http://www.ifex.org/2001/09/25/at_pakistan_afghanistan_border/ |archive-date=September 12, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Donald DiFranco, TV engineer for [[WABC-TV]], WTC (North Tower)<ref name=ifex2001 /> \n* Steve Jacobson, TV engineer for [[WPIX|WPIX-TV]], WTC (North Tower)<ref name=ifex2001 /> \n* Bob Pattison, TV engineer for [[WCBS-TV]], WTC (North Tower)<ref name=CBS2001 /><ref name=ifex2001 />\n* Thomas Pecorelli, professional freelance photojournalist, American Airlines Flight 11 passenger<ref name=CBS2001 />\n* Isias Rivera, TV engineer for WCBS-TV, WTC (North Tower)<ref name=CBS2001 /><ref name=ifex2001 />\n* William Steckman, TV engineer for [[WNBC|WNBC-TV]], WTC (North Tower)<ref name=ifex2001 />\n\n== Gallery ==\n{{Commons category|Journalists killed in the United States}}\n{{Gallery\n| title = Journalists killed in the United States\n|File:Appletons' Lovejoy Elijah Parish.jpg|alt1=Elijah Parish Lovejoy (portrait)|<center>Elijah Parish Lovejoy</center>\n|File:James King of William, San Francisco editor.gif|alt2=James King of William (portrait)|<center>James King of William</center>\n|File:FrederickWadsworthLoring.jpg|alt3=Frederick Wadsworth Loring (portrait)|<center>Frederick Wadsworth Loring</center>\n|File:Markkellogg.jpg|alt4=Mark Kellogg (portrait)|<center>Mark Kellogg</center>\n|File:Charles de Young.jpg|alt5=Charles de Young (portrait)|<center>Charles de Young</center>\n|File:WCBrann.jpg|alt6=William Cowper Brann (portrait)|<center>William Cowper Brann</center>\n|File:Edward Ward Carmack.jpg|alt7=Edward Ward Carmack (portrait)|<center>Edward Ward Carmack</center>\n|File:Walter W Liggett.jpg|alt8=Walter W Liggett (portrait)|<center>Walter W Liggett</center>\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Censorship in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Journalists killed in the United States}}\n[[Category:Assassinated American journalists| ]]\n[[Category:Murder in the United States]]\n[[Category:Death in the United States-related lists|Journalists killed]]\n[[Category:Lists of journalists killed|United States]]\n[[Category:Lists of victims of crimes]]\n[[Category:United States crime-related lists]]\n[[Category:Censorship in the United States]]\n[[Category:Human rights in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n\nNumerous journalists have been murdered or killed in the United States while reporting, covering a military conflict, or because of their status as a journalist.  At least 39 of these have been directly targeted as a result of their journalistic investigations.<ref name=peele>{{cite news|first=Thomas |last=Peele |title=Death stalks some reporters working their beats in U.S.|url=http://www.cleveland.com/opinion/index.ssf/2012/08/death_stalks_some_reporters_wo.html |newspaper=Plain Dealer |date=August 1, 2012|accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref> The most recent journalists killed in the United States were four reporters for ''[[The Capital]]'' in [[Annapolis, Maryland]], who were killed on June 28, 2018 in a  [[Capital Gazette shooting|mass shooting at the newspaper's office]].\n\nThe most dangerous sector of the [[United States|US]] media after 1980 has been the race and ethnic press.<ref name=newsweek>{{cite magazine|first=Peter |last=Katel |title=A Rash of Media Murders |magazine=Newsweek |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/1993/07/04/a-rash-of-media-murders.html |archiveurl=http://peterkatel.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/nwk_93_07_05.pdf |date=July 5, 1993 |archivedate=December 2011 |accessdate=October 21, 2013}}</ref><ref name=sfgate>{{cite news|first=Matthai |last=Kuruvila |title=Grassroots ethnic reporting a perilous calling |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date= January 31, 2008 |accessdate=November 6, 2013 |url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Grassroots-ethnic-reporting-a-perilous-calling-3230086.php}}</ref>  According to the [[Committee to Protect Journalists]], ten journalists serving the Vietnamese, Haitian and Chinese immigrant communities were killed in political assassinations between 1980 and 1993.<ref name=ajr>{{cite web |last=Stacy |first=Stacy Lu |url=http://www.ajr.org/article.asp?id=3564 |title=Journalism for the Brave &#124; American Journalism Review |publisher=Ajr.org |date=June 1996 |accessdate=November 16, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021215659/http://www.ajr.org/article.asp?id=3564 |archive-date=October 21, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=ajr1993>{{cite news |first=Eliza Newlin |last=Carney |title=The Dangers of Being A Vietnamese Reporter |publisher=American Journalism Review |url=http://www.ajr.org/Article.asp?id=1998 |date=November 1993 |accessdate=December 6, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021220012/http://www.ajr.org/Article.asp?id=1998 |archive-date=October 21, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=propublica1>{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/terror-in-little-saigon-vietnam-american-journalists-murdered|title=Terror in Little Saigon|first=A.C.|last=Thompson|work=ProPublica & Frontline |date=November 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Chauncey Bailey]], who was the editor at a large circulation African American newspaper, was murdered in 2007 for his investigative reporting.<ref name=sfgate2007 />\n\nSince the [[September 11 attacks]], terrorism-related deaths involving journalists is another trend.<ref>{{cite web|first=Joel |last=Simon |title=Attacks on the Press in 2008: Introduction |publisher=Committee to Protect Journalists |date=February 10, 2009 |accessdate=March 1, 2013 |url=http://cpj.org/2009/02/attacks-on-the-press-in-2008-introduction.php}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Ken |last=Guggenheim |newspaper=Editor & Publisher |title=Memorial Adds Names of 51 Journalists |date=May 6, 2002 |accessdate=March 1, 2013 |url=http://www.editorandpublisher.com/Archive/Memorial-Adds-Names-Of-51-Journalists}}</ref>\n\nIn some cases, journalists have been attacked but survived, such as [[Victor Riesel]].<ref name=\"obitNYT\">{{cite news|first=Van |last=Gelder |title=Victor Riesel, 81, Columnist Blinded by Acid Attack, Dies |newspaper=New York Times |date=January 5, 1995 |accessdate=June 6, 2013 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/01/05/obituaries/victor-riesel-81-columnist-blinded-by-acid-attack-dies.html}}</ref>\n\n== List ==\n\n{{expand list|date=May 2013}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Name !! Employer !! Location !! Notes\n|-\n|{{dts|November 7, 1837}}||[[Elijah Parish Lovejoy]]||''[[Alton Observer]]''||[[Alton, Illinois|Alton]], [[Illinois]]||This abolition editor was killed by a mob supporting slavery in the Union.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elijah Parish Lovejoy |work=The Untold Story: Activism & Social Justice at Colby | url=http://www.colby.edu/education/activism/stories/lovejoy.html |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Elijah Parish Lovejoy |url=http://www.altonweb.com/history/lovejoy/ |publisher=Altonweb at the Riverbend |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|June 6, 1843}}||James Hagan||''Vicksburg Sentinel''||[[Vicksburg, Mississippi|Vicksburg]], [[Mississippi]]||Hagan was killed in a duel by [[Daniel Weisiger Adams]]-the son of a man he had criticized in his newspaper.<ref name=DavisPapers1 /><ref name=DavisPapers2 /><ref name=DavisPapers3>{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Jefferson|title=The Papers of Jefferson Davis: Volume 2 June 1841 \u2013 July 1846|year=1974|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|pages=318\u2013319|editor=James T. McIntosh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=A Crime Scene: Vicksburg, Mississippi |work=The Trans-Mississippian |url=http://transmississippian.blogspot.com/2012/06/crime-scene-vicksburg-mississippi.html |format=blog |date=June 3, 2012 |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|February 29, 1844}}||James A. Ryan||''Vicksburg Sentinel''||Vicksburg, Mississippi||The Vicksburg Sentinel was a Democratic paper and Ryan was killed by his rival Whig counterpart in a duel on their second fight.<ref name=DavisPapers2>{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Jefferson|title=The Papers of Jefferson Davis: Volume 2 June 1841 \u2013 July 1846|year=1974|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|pages=62|editor=James T. McIntosh}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|September 15, 1848}}||John Jenkins||''Vicksburg Sentinel''||Vicksburg, Mississippi||Killed in a fight with an attorney after the two had a previous altercation.<ref name=DavisPapers1>{{cite book|last=Davis|first=Jefferson|title=The Papers of Jefferson Davis: Volume 2 June 1841 \u2013 July 1846|year=1974|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|pages=252\u2013253|editor=James T. McIntosh}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|June 22, 1854}}||Joseph Mansfield||''San Joaquin Republican''||[[Stockton, California|Stockton]], [[California]]||Mansfield was killed in a fight with a rival editor, both of whom were Democrats.<ref>{{cite news|first=Doug |last=Noble |title=Criminal annals 93: Gold fields and Judge Lynch |url=http://www.mtdemocrat.com/archived-stories/criminal-annals-93-gold-fields-and-judge-lynch/ |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|May 20, 1856}}||[[James King of William]]||''Daily Evening Bulletin''||[[San Francisco]], California||<ref>{{cite web|first=James P. |last=Casey |title=Assassination of James King of Wm.: San Francisco, May 14th, 1856 |url=http://www.sfmuseum.net/hist6/corahang.html |publisher=The Virtual Museum of the City of San Francisco |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Lell Hawley |last=Woolley |url=http://www.books-about-california.com/Pages/California_1849_1913/California_1849_1913_text.html |title=California 1849\u20131913 or The Rambling Sketches and Experiences of Sixty-Four Years' Residence in That State |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|April 6, 1862}}||[[Irving W. Carson]]||''[[New-York Tribune]]''||[[Pittsburg Landing, Tennessee|Pittsburg Landing]], [[Tennessee]]||First journalist to be killed during the U.S. Civil War. Killed by a cannonball fire while covering the [[Battle of Shiloh]] and [[Ulysses S. Grant|General Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Heidler|first=David Stephen|title=Encyclopedia of the American Civil War: A Political, Social, and Military|year=2000|publisher=W.W. Norton|location=New York|pages=426\u2013427|author2=Jeanne T. Heidler |author3=David J. Coles  }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|June 23, 1863}}||Lynde Walter Buckingham||''New York Herald''||[[Aldie, Virginia|Aldie]], [[Virginia]]||Killed as a result of an ambush during the [[U.S. Civil War]]. He was buried at the Mount Zion Old School Baptist Church-VDHR 53-339 in Aldie.<ref>{{cite web |title=Did you know? |work=Mosby Heritage Area Association Newsletter |publisher=Mosby Heritage Area Association |url=http://www.mosbyheritagearea.org/Enewsletter/EnewsFeb10.html |format=newsletter |date=February 2010 |accessdate=December 7, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803201013/http://mosbyheritagearea.org/Enewsletter/EnewsFeb10.html |archive-date=August 3, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|October 6, 1863}}||[[James R. O'Neill (correspondent)|James O'Neal]]||''[[Frank Leslie's Illustrated Newspaper]]''||[[Baxter Springs, Kansas|Baxter Springs]], [[Kansas]]||O'Neal was an artist-correspondent murdered by Quantrill's guerrillas at the [[Battle of Baxter Springs|Baxter Springs Massacre]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Nichols|first=Bruce |title=Guerrilla Warfare in Civil War Missouri, Volume II, 1863|year=2004|publisher=McFarland |location= |url=}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|May 6, 1864}}||Samuel Fiske (aka Dunn Browne)||''[[The Republican (Springfield, Massachusetts)|Springfield Republican]]''||[[Fredericksburg, Virginia|Fredericksburg]], Virginia||Capt. Fiske wrote under the name Dunn Browne and served in the army and was mortally wounded at the [[Battle of the Wilderness]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Fiske|first=Samuel |title=Mr. Dunn Browne's Experiences in the Army|year=1866|publisher=Nichols and Noyes |location=Boston |url=https://archive.org/details/experiencesinar00fiskgoog |quote=Samuel Wheelock Fiske.|accessdate=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|September 14, 1866}}||Ridgeway Glover||''[[Frank Leslie's Illustrated Newspaper]]''||[[Fort Phil Kearny]], [[Wyoming]]||While covering the [[American Indian Wars]], Glover was killed and mutilated during the construction of Fort Kearny in 1866.<ref>{{cite news|title=Indian outrages |publisher={{Subscription required|via=[[New York Times]]}} |work=New York Times |date=September 27, 1866 |accessdate=May 14, 2013 |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0E12FB3E59137A93C5AB1782D85F428684F9}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|November 5, 1871}}||[[Frederick Wadsworth Loring]]||''[[Appleton's Magazine|Appleton's Journal]]''||[[Wickenburg, Arizona|Wickenburg]], [[Arizona]]||Was killed while on assignment out west in what is known as the [[Wickenburg Massacre]], an attack on a stagecoach by Native Americans.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Pacific Coast, 1871: Frederick W. Loring's Death |newspaper=Hartford Daily Courant |date=November 15, 1871 |id={{ProQuest|553691910}} }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|June 25, 1876}}||[[Mark Kellogg (reporter)|Mark Kellogg]]||[[Associated Press]]||[[Little Bighorn Battlefield National Monument|Little Bighorn Battlefield]], [[Montana]]||The first Associated Press journalist to die while reporting.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Marlane A. |last=Liddell |title=The AP Looks Back: 150 Years of Capturing the Moment |url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history-archaeology/ap.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130202095642/http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history-archaeology/ap.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-02-02 |magazine=Smithsonian Magazine |date=May 1998 |access-date=December 7, 2012 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|March 27, 1877}}||J. Clarke Swayze||''[[The Topeka Capital-Journal|Topeka Daily Blade]]''||[[Topeka, Kansas|Topeka]], Kansas||Swayze was killed after publishing a critical article about his murderer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Topeka:John W. Wilson, who shot J. Clarke Swayze |newspaper=Western Home Journal |date=April 5, 1877 |accessdate=May 14, 2013 |url=http://www.kansasnewspapers.org/article.php?id=1585}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|April 23, 1880}}||[[Charles de Young]]||''[[San Francisco Chronicle|The Daily Dramatic Chronicle]]''||San Francisco, California||With his brother [[M. H. de Young]], he founded the newspaper that would become the ''San Francisco Chronicle''. The mayor's son killed him in revenge for a feud de Young had with his father.<ref>{{cite journal|last=McKee |first=Irving |title=The Shooting of Charles de Young |journal=Pacific Historical Review | date=August 1947 |volume=16 |issue=3 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|November 17, 1881}}||A. B. Thornton||''Boonville News''||[[Boonville, Missouri|Boonville]], [[Missouri]]||The town marshal killed Thornton because of criticism from the newspaper and won acquittal based on the perception that the criticism was too intense.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crimes and casualties |newspaper=The Sun |date=November 21, 1881 |id={{ProQuest|534607699}} }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|March 27, 1884}}||Charles L. Kusz||''The Gringo and Greaser''||[[Manzano, New Mexico|Manzano]], [[New Mexico]]||Shot through his window by unknown gunman on horses. His newspaper was reform oriented and created enemies as it sought changes.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawless New Mexico |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=April 22, 1889 |id={{ProQuest|163457579}} }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|May 5, 1887}}||Roderick D. Gambrell||''The Shield and Sword''||[[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]], Mississippi||Shot by Colonel Jones S. Hamilton for publishing allegations of corrupt business practices Hamilton was engaged in with the state of Mississippi. Hamilton was shot by Gambrell, but survived and was later acquitted of his murder by a jury.<ref>[https://yesteryearsnews.wordpress.com/2010/10/11/roderick-d-gambrell-death-of-a-hip-pocket-reformer/ Roderick D. Gambrell: Death of a Hip Pocket Reformer \u2013 YesterYear Once More] Retrieved November 6, 2016.</ref><ref>[https://yesteryearsnews.wordpress.com/2010/10/12/colonel-jones-stewart-hamilton-the-train-and-the-tragedies/ Colonel Jones Stewart Hamilton: The Train and the Tragedies \u2013 YesterYear Once More] Retrieved November 6, 2016.</ref><ref name=Worse>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lgRYuftJ6wQC&pg=PA49&lpg#v=onepage&q&f=false |last=Oshinsky |first=David M. |date=1996 |title=Worse Than Slavery: Parchman Farm and the Ordeal of Jim Crow Justice |location=New York |publisher=Simon & Schuster |pages=49\u201350 |isbn=978-0-684-82298-3}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|May 1, 1888}}||John H. Martin||''New Mississippian''||Jackson, Mississippi||Shot in a street encounter with ex-[[Confederate Army|Confederate]] General [[William Wirt Adams|Wirt Adams]], who was also shot and killed by Martin. Martin published numerous attacks on Adams's character in part due to his association with Colonel Hamilton, killer of the aforementioned Roderick D. Gambrell.<ref name=Worse /><ref>[https://yesteryearsnews.wordpress.com/2010/10/05/the-double-death-which-disgraced-mississippi/ THE DOUBLE DEATH 