o, California||The Chinese national was murdered while visiting the United States. The case remained unsolved but [[Kuomintang]] (KMT) supporters were suspected of carrying out the assassination at the Shanghai Low restaurant.<ref>{{cite book|title=Chinese American Transnational Politics |first= H. Mark |last=Lai |publisher=University of Illinois Press |year=2010 |page=14}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|July 16, 1927}}||[[Don Mellett]]||''Canton Daily News''||[[Canton, Ohio|Canton]], Ohio||Shot to death in his garage as a result of a conspiracy with a crime boss and the police chief of Canton.<ref name=peele />\n|-\n|{{dts|June 9, 1930}}||[[Jake Lingle]]||''[[Chicago Tribune]]''||[[Chicago]], Illinois||Killed in gangland-style by associates of [[Al Capone]]. In addition to his job as a reporter, Lingle was on the payroll of Capone's criminal organization.<ref name=\"chicagoreader\">{{cite news |url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/where-in-the-world-is-molly-zelko/Content?oid=881563 | title=Where in the World Is Molly Zelko? | newspaper=Chicago Reader |date=March 11, 1993 |accessdate=May 2, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|July 23, 1930}}||[[Jerry Buckley (journalist)|Jerry Buckley]]||[[WDTK|WMBC-AM]]||[[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]||Gunned down on election night.<ref name=\"time1\">{{cite magazine |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,739981,00.html | title=Death in Detroit | magazine=Time |date=August 4, 1930 |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|September 6, 1934}}||Howard Guilford||''[[The Saturday Press (Minneapolis)|The Saturday Press]]''||[[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]]||Editor of a newspaper that exposed corruption and organized crime. He and partner Jay Near won the US Supreme Court decision in [[Near v. Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |title=Former newspaper editor is slain |publisher=Lewiston Evening Journal |date=September 7, 1934 | accessdate=December 7, 2012 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1913&dat=19340907&id=nsQgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=_2kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5255,5059856}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=United Press |title=Gag law case editor is slain |publisher=Milwaukee Journal |date=September 7, 1934 | accessdate=December 7, 2012 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AalQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6CEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6841,3464593&dq=howard+guilford&hl=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|December 9, 1935}}||[[Walter Liggett]]||''Midwest American''||Minneapolis, Minnesota||He wrote about political corruption and organized crime.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liggett slaying stirs demand for clean-up |publisher=Milwaukee Journal |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=faBQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PSIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4181,2151814&dq=walter+liggett&hl=en |date=December 15, 1935 |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|agency=Associated Press |title=Walter Liggett, editor, killed |newspaper=St. Petersburg Times |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UVJPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4E0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4257,5199306&dq=walter+liggett&hl=en |date=December 10, 1935 |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|January 11, 1943}}||[[Carlo Tresca]]||''Il Martello'' (The Hammer)||[[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]||Radical socialist newspaper editor and labor activist; believed to have been killed by a [[Sicilian Mafia|Mafia]] hitman.<ref name=\"NYdailynews\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/unsolved-murder-famous-anarchist-carlo-tresca-article-1.790137 | title=The unsolved murder of famous anarchist Carlo Tresca | newspaper=New York Daily News |date=August 14, 2017 |accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|January 22, 1945}}||[[Arthur Kasherman]]||''Public Press'' (alternative)||Minneapolis, Minnesota||His death <!-- at E. 15th St & Chicago Ave S near North Central University ---> figured into [[Hubert Humphrey|Hubert Humphrey's]] mayoral victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=The murder of journalist Arthur Kasherman |url=http://www.rubbedout.net/ |work=Rubbed Out |date=November 21, 2009 |access-date=December 7, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110108024555/http://www.rubbedout.net/ |archive-date=January 8, 2011 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|July 29, 1949}}||[[Murder of Bill Mason|W.H. \"Bill\" Mason]]||KBKI (AM)||[[Alice, Texas|Alice]], Texas||Known as a crusading radio journalist in a county ruled with an iron hand by local law enforcement, Mason was shot dead by Sheriff deputy Sam Smithwick, who Mason had publicly accused of running a strip club. The senate candidate who lost to [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] believed that Smithwick had information about how the election had been rigged but Smithwick was hanged before their meeting. Mason's tombstone reads: \"He had the nerve to tell the truth for a lot of little people.\"<ref name=peele /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GB8hAAAAIBAJ&sjid=p2QEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2698,2953697&dq=southwick+alice+mason&hl=en |title=Dime a dance place is shot up after slaying |newspaper=Sarasota Herald-Tribune |date=July 31, 1949 |accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1917&dat=19520527&id=tIguAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yoAFAAAAIBAJ&pg=955,3883574 |title=On disputed Texas election |newspaper=Schenectady Gazette |date=May 27, 1952 |accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Alicia |last=Salinas |title=Alice, Texas |work=Handbook of Texas Online |publisher=Texas State Historical Association |url=http://www.tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/hea01 |accessdate=January 12, 2013|date=2010-06-09 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|September 30, 1962}}||[[Paul Guihard]]||''[[Agence France-Presse]]''||[[Oxford, Mississippi|Oxford]], Mississippi||Guihard was a British-French citizen who was killed during the civil rights era at the [[University of Mississippi]]. He was assigned to photograph the events surrounding [[James Meredith|James Meredith's]] attendance when he turned his focus on riots and in the confusion was shot. His murder remains an unsolved case.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Bryant |first= Nick |date=Autumn 2006 |title= Black Man Who Was Crazy Enough to Apply to Ole Miss |journal=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education |volume= |issue= 53 |pages= 60\u201371 |url= |quote= |doi= }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|August 29, 1970}}||[[Rub\u00e9n Salazar]]||''[[Los Angeles Times]]''||[[Los Angeles]], California||Salazar was killed by deputies of the [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]] while covering the [[Chicano Moratorium]] protest in [[East Los Angeles (region)|East Los Angeles]].  The park where the protest took place was later renamed [[Salazar Park]] in his honor.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/ci_15928350 |title=Ruben Salazar killing left impact on Hispanics, journalism |author=Gustavo Reveles Acosta |date=August 29, 2010 |newspaper=El Paso Times |access-date=September 3, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130110221358/http://www.elpasotimes.com/ci_15928350 |archive-date=January 10, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=A People's Guide to Los Angeles|author1=Laura Pulido|author2=Laura Barraclough|author3=Wendy Cheng|publisher=University of California Press|place=Berkeley|year=2012|isbn=9780520270817|page=4}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|June 2, 1976}}||[[Don Bolles]]||''[[The Arizona Republic|Arizona Republic]]''||[[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]], Arizona||Murdered by a car bomb. Initially assumed to have been a mafia hit,<ref>{{cite news|title=Don Bolles' tragic death|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VP9JAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DR4NAAAAIBAJ&pg=3922,2003692&dq=don+bolles&hl=en |newspaper=Michigan Daily|date=June 16, 1976|accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Tatiana |last=Hensley |url=https://www.azcentral.com/specials/special01/0528bolles-profile.html |title=Bolles: Cautious man, dedicated journalist |newspaper=Arizona Republic|date=May 28, 2006|accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Charles|last=Kelly |url=https://www.azcentral.com/specials/special01/articles/0528Bolles-Intro28.html |title=Reverberations felt 30 years after Don Bolles' death |newspaper=Arizona Republic|date=May 28, 2006|accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref> three local men were later convicted of his death. The motive was determined to have been feared exposure of involvement in a land fraud scheme.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Richard|last=Ruelas|date=July 6, 2016|title=James Robison, accused of bombing Republic reporter Don Bolles in 1976, dead at 90|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/phoenix/2016/07/06/james-robison-accused-bombing-republic-reporter-don-bolles-1976-dead-90/86001272|website=The Arizona Republic|access-date=October 20, 2016|quote=The Republic confirmed Robison's death this week when it obtained a death certificate from the San Bernardino County clerk\u2019s office, showing he died in 2013 at age 90.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | author=Glen Creno and Dennis Wagner | url=http://archive.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/local/articles/2009/07/22/20090722dunlap0722.html | title=Max Dunlap dies; was guilty of killing \"Republic\" reporter | website=[[The Arizona Republic]] | date=July 22, 2009 | access-date=October 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>[[Associated Press]], [http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue2/2002/05/27/100944-notorious-76-bombing-figure-dies/ Notorious '76 bombing figure dies], reprinted in the ''[[Tucson Citizen]]'' (May 27, 2002).  Retrieved 2016-10-16.</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|March 9, 1977}}||[[Maurice Williams (journalist)|Maurice Williams]]||[[WHUR-FM]]||[[Washington, D.C.]]||He was murdered during the [[1977 Hanafi Siege]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Theresa |last=Vargas |title='Some Things You Never Forget': Thirty years ago, gunmen stormed three D.C. buildings, taking 150 hostages and one life | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/11/AR2007031101562.html |newspaper=Washington Post | page=B01 | date=March 12, 2007 |accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{dts|June 28, 1978}}||[[John A. Kelly]]||[[WHDH-TV]]